rea and Kenya as of 26 Sept. 2008 |url=https://digitallibrary.un.org/record/1325971?ln=en&v=pdf |access-date=23 November 2024 |website=United Nations Digital Library | date=September 26, 2008 }}</ref>\n|-\n|157\n|{{Flag|South Sudan}}\n|{{dts|18 November 2011}}\n|-\n|}\n\n===Other relations===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!#\n!Country\n!Date\n|-\n|1\n|{{Flag|France}}\n|{{Date table sorting|October 2011}}<ref>{{cite web | title=NORTH KOREA/FRANCE • New cell at UNESCO - 30/06/2011 | date=June 28, 2011 | url=https://www.intelligenceonline.com/government-intelligence/2011/06/30/new-cell-at-unesco,91014427-art }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=North Korea's French Connection | date=January 23, 2014 | url=https://www.38north.org/2014/01/afostercarter012314/ }}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n== Bilateral relations ==\n\n=== Africa ===\n{{Main|Africa–North Korea relations}}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:100%; margin:auto;\" !style=\"width:15%;\" \n! style=\"width:15%;\" |Country\n! style=\"width:12%;\" |Formal Relations Began\n!Notes\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Algeria}}\n|<!--Date started--> 1962 (July 3)\n|On September 25, 1958, the National Liberation Front of Algeria had started relations with North Korea.  Upon independence on July 5, 1962, [[Algeria]] became the first non-Marxist–Leninist country to establish diplomatic relations with North Korea.{{sfn|Wertz|Oh|Kim|2016|p=3}} Initially, relations were with the [[National Liberation Front (Algeria)|National Liberation Front]] since the [[Algerian War]] was still ongoing and the country had not gained its independence yet.{{sfn|Wertz|Oh|Kim|2016|pp=3, 8fa}} North Korea maintains an embassy in the country.{{sfn|Wertz|Oh|Kim|2016|p=2}}\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Angola}}\n|<!--Date started-->\n|North Korea has had a strong relationship with [[Angola]] from the time of Angola's struggle for independence. It is estimated that 3,000 North Korean troops and a thousand advisers took part in the [[Angolan Civil War]] in the 1970s and 1980s, and fighting against the [[apartheid]] South African military.<ref name=\"Young\" /> In 2011, Angola purchased naval patrol boats from North Korea.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nknews.org/2016/04/angola-discusses-public-security-cooperation-with-north-korea/|title=Angola discusses public security cooperation with North Korea|last=Macdonald|first=Hamish|date=April 8, 2016|work=[[NK News]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160525084901/https://www.nknews.org/2016/04/angola-discusses-public-security-cooperation-with-north-korea/|archive-date=May 25, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Benin}}\n|<!--Date started-->\n|After the [[People's Republic of Benin]] was proclaimed in 1975, the government established good relations with several Communist countries, including North Korea. These good relations have continued to the present day.<ref name=\"Hotham\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nknews.org/2013/08/n-korea-strengthens-ties-with-cameroon-other-african-countries/|title=N. Korea strengthens ties with Cameroon, other African countries|last=Hotham|first=Oliver|date=August 23, 2013|work=[[NK News]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160623215214/https://www.nknews.org/2013/08/n-korea-strengthens-ties-with-cameroon-other-african-countries/|archive-date=June 23, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Botswana}}\n|<!--Date started-->\n|See [[Botswana–North Korea relations]]{{pb}}[[Botswana]] had good relations with North Korea from 1974.<ref>{{cite book|title=North Korea Handbook|last=Yonhap News Agency|date=2002|publisher=[[M. E. Sharpe]]|isbn=978-076-563-523-5|location=[[Seoul]]|page=967|author-link=Yonhap}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Asian Almanac|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|date=1997|publisher=V.T. Sambandan|page=8140}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Summary of World Broadcasts: Far East, Part 3|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|date=1976|publisher=[[BBC|British Broadcasting Corporation]]|location=[[London]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Transformative Political Leadership: Making a Difference in the Developing World|last=Rotberg|first=Robert I.|date=2012|publisher=[[University of Chicago Press]]|isbn=978-022-672-898-8|location=[[Chicago]]|page=86}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=A Pied Cloak: Memoirs of a Colonial Police Officer (special Branch), Kenya, 1953–66, Bahrain, 1967–71, Lesotho, 1971–75, Botswana, 1976–81|last=Franklin|first=Derek Peter|date=1996|publisher=Janus Publishing Company|isbn=978-185-756-294-1|location=[[Cambridge]]|page=157}}</ref> In years that followed, the first independent leader of Botswana, President [[Seretse Khama]], made a state visit to [[Pyongyang]], and several North Korean [[martial arts]] instructors were commissioned to train the [[Botswana Police Service]] in unarmed combat but did not stay long. Beyond this, North Korea used the [[Mansudae Overseas Projects]] company to build the [[Three Dikgosi Monument]], which has been a source of controversy in the [[Western media]], and hired medical professionals to supplement the ones in their country.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sundaystandard.info/article.php/article.php?NewsID=19583&GroupID=1|title=North Korea built Three Dikgosi Monument Bashi Letsididi|date=March 30, 2014|newspaper=Sunday Standard|access-date=January 5, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150106003601/http://www.sundaystandard.info/article.php/article.php?NewsID=19583&GroupID=1|archive-date=January 6, 2015|url-status=dead|location=[[Gaborone]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Migration and the Globalisation of Health Care: The Health Worker Exodus?|last=Connell|first=John|date=2010|publisher=[[Edward Elgar Publishing]]|isbn=978-184-980-518-6|location=[[Cheltenham]]|page=213}}</ref>{{pb}}However, Botswana broke off diplomatic ties in 2014, after suspending bilateral cooperation the previous year, over alleged human rights violations.<ref name=\"suspension of diplomatic relations\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gov.bw/en/Ministries--Authorities/Ministries/Ministry-of-Foreign-Affairs-and-International-Cooperation/News/BOTSWANA-CUT-TIES-WITH-NORTH-KOREA/|title=Botswana Cuts Ties with North Korea|date=February 20, 2014|website=gov.bw|publisher=[[Politics of Botswana|Ministry of Foreign Affairs and International Cooperation]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150106001946/http://www.gov.bw/en/Ministries--Authorities/Ministries/Ministry-of-Foreign-Affairs-and-International-Cooperation/News/BOTSWANA-CUT-TIES-WITH-NORTH-KOREA/|archive-date=January 6, 2015|url-status=dead|access-date=January 5, 2015}}</ref> In the following year, [[Ian Khama]], the president of Botswana, declared that the country was an \"opponent\" and went on to claim that \"the aggressive attitude of North Korea threatens peace in the region and therefore threatens world peace&nbsp;... I think the North Korean leadership is living in the Stone Age.\"<ref>Yonhap News, [http://www.yonhapnews.co.kr/bulletin/2015/10/23/0200000000AKR20151023161000043.HTML Botswana President \"North Korean human rights retreat, relationship was not worth keeping\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170211080502/http://www.yonhapnews.co.kr/bulletin/2015/10/23/0200000000AKR20151023161000043.HTML |date=February 11, 2017 }}, October 2015.</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Burkina Faso}}\n|<!--Date started-->\n|See [[Burkina Faso–North Korea relations]]{{pb}}[[Burkina Faso]] and North Korea established strong relations during the Cold War, and these have been continued.{{pb}}Relations between [[Burkina Faso]] and North Korea have historically been relatively close. Neither country maintains an embassy in the other, although North Korea used to have an ambassador in [[Ouagadougou]].<ref name=\"Handbook\">{{cite book|title=North Korea Handbook|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|date=2002|publisher=[[M. E. Sharpe]]|isbn=978-076-563-523-5|location=[[Armonk, New York|Armonk]]|pages=902, 926}}<!--|access-date=6 November 2014--></ref> Relations were especially close during the [[Cold War]], with North Korea providing military equipment to the [[Military of Burkina Faso|army]] of the [[Republic of Upper Volta]], along with agricultural, military and technical assistance over the years.<ref>{{cite book|title=Rogue Regime: Kim Jong Il and the Looming Threat of North Korea|url=https://archive.org/details/rogueregimekimjo00beck|url-access=registration|last=Becker|first=Jasper|date=2005|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|isbn=978-019-803-810-8|location=[[Oxford]]|page=[https://archive.org/details/rogueregimekimjo00beck/page/149 149]|author-link=Jasper Becker}}<!--|access-date=6 November 2014--></ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Hungry for Peace: International Security, Humanitarian Assistance, and Social Change in North Korea|last=Smith|first=Hazel|date=2005|publisher=[[United States Institute of Peace|United States Institute of Peace Press]]|isbn=978-192-922-358-9|location=[[Washington, D.C.]]|page=164}}<!--|access-date=6 November 2014--></ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Divided dynamism: the diplomacy of separated nations: Germany, Korea, China|last=Metzler|first=John J.|date=1996|publisher=[[University Press of America]]|isbn=978-076-180-235-8|location=[[Lanham, Maryland|Lanham]]|page=101}}<!--|access-date=6 November 2014--></ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Asian Almanac: Weekly Abstract of Asian Affairs|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|date=1983|publisher=V.T. Sambandan|location=[[Singapore]]|page=11792}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Summary of World Broadcasts: Far East|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|date=1985|publisher=[[BBC|British Broadcasting Corporation]]|location=[[London]]}}</ref> [[Thomas Sankara]], a [[Marxist]] and revolutionary, visited [[Pyongyang]] several times, leading to a DPRK–Burkina Faso Friendship Association in place at the time. During the reign of [[Blaise Compaoré]], the successor of Sankara, cultural and trade relations remained strong, along with North Korea completing construction, in 1998, five small water reservoirs in the country.<ref>{{cite book|title=Historical Dictionary of Burkina Faso|last1=Rupley|first1=Lawrence|last2=Bangali|first2=Lamissa|last3=Diamitani|first3=Boureima|date=2013|publisher=[[Rowman & Littlefield|Scarecrow Press]]|isbn=978-081-088-010-8|location=[[Lanham, Maryland|Lanham]]|page=57}}<!--|access-date=6 November 2014--></ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Pyongyang-Sponsored \"People's Theater\" Completed in Burkina Faso|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|date=1988|newspaper=Naewoe Press|location=[[Seoul]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Statistical Appendix to Minerals Yearbook|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|date=1988|publisher=[[United States Government Printing Office]]|location=[[Washington, D.C.]]|page=325}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://kcnawatch.nknews.org/article/ceb0|title=Reservoirs built in Burkina Faso with DPRK help|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|date=January 22, 1998|access-date=November 6, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141106045436/http://kcnawatch.nknews.org/article/ceb0|archive-date=November 6, 2014|url-status=dead|agency=[[Korean Central News Agency]]|location=[[Pyongyang]]}}</ref>{{pb}}In recent years, Burkina Faso has strayed from traditional relations with North Korea, by voting, in 2009, in favor of [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 1874]], which imposed further economic sanctions on North Korea, saying that they voted in such a manner due to their commitment to a \"[[Anti-nuclear movement|nuclear weapon-free]]\" world.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.un.org/News/Press/docs//2009/sc9679.doc.htm|title=Text of United Nations Security Council Resolution 1874|publisher=UN Press Centre|access-date=June 28, 2017|archive-date=September 5, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140905002934/http://www.un.org/News/Press/docs/2009/sc9679.doc.htm|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Burundi}}\n|<!--Date started-->2011\n|See [[Burundi–North Korea relations]]{{pb}}[[Burundi]] and North Korea have good relations. In 2011, Burundi purchased weapons from North Korea. In 2016, North Korea's [[Kim Yong-nam]] visited Burundi.<ref name=\"Ramani\">{{cite magazine|last=Ramani|first=Samuel|date=June 4, 2016|title=North Korea's African Allies|url=https://thediplomat.com/2016/06/north-koreas-african-allies/|url-status=live|magazine=The Diplomat|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160609083839/https://thediplomat.com/2016/06/north-koreas-african-allies/|archive-date=June 9, 2016}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Central African Republic}}\n|<!--Date started-->1969\n|See [[Central African Republic–North Korea relations]]{{pb}}From 1969, North Korea maintained a close relationship with the long-time military ruler of the [[Central African Republic]], [[Jean-Bédel Bokassa]], even though he was [[Anti-communism|anti-communist]].<ref>{{cite book|title=North Korea Handbook|last=Yonhap News Agency|date=2002|publisher=[[M. E. Sharpe]]|isbn=978-076-563-523-5|location=[[Seoul]]|page=957|author-link=Yonhap}}<!--|access-date=26 December 2014 --></ref> After he proclaimed himself Emperor in 1976, Bokassa's first foreign visit was to Pyongyang, returning to the country in 1978, signing a treaty of peace and friendship with [[Kim Il Sung]].{{sfn|Armstrong|2013|p={{page needed|date=September 2021}}}}<ref>{{cite book|title=Dark Age: The Political Odyssey of Emperor Bokassa|last=Titley|first=Brian|date=2002|publisher=[[McGill-Queen's University Press]]|isbn=978-077-352-418-7|page=102}}<!--|access-date=26 December 2014 --></ref> Even after Bokassa was overthrown in 1979, friendly relations continued. By March 1986 it was estimated that North Korea was supplying 13 technicians to the Central African Republic, seemingly to counter [[South Korea]]n influence in the country.<ref>{{cite book|title=Korea versus Korea: A Case of Contested Legitimacy|last=Gills|first=Barry|date=2005|publisher=[[Routledge]]|isbn=978-113-476-625-3|location=[[London]]}}<!--|access-date=26 December 2014 --></ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Comoros}}\n|<!--Date started--> 1975 (November 13)\n|See [[Comoros–North Korea relations]]{{pb}}North Korea has had diplomatic relations with the [[Comoros]] since November 13, 1975.{{sfn|Wertz|Oh|Kim|2016|p=8}}\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Democratic Republic of the Congo}}\n|<!--Date started-->\n|The [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]] has friendly relations with North Korea. After the death of [[Laurent Kabila]], North Korean workers under the [[Mansudae Overseas Projects]] constructed a statue commemorating the life of the former leader in [[Kinshasa]].<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Monument to African Dictator Laurent Kabila|url=http://www.atlasobscura.com/places/monument-to-african-dictator-laurent-kabila|url-status=live|magazine=[[Atlas Obscura]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160430010356/http://www.atlasobscura.com/places/monument-to-african-dictator-laurent-kabila|archive-date=April 30, 2016}}</ref> When a North Korean delegation visited DR Congo in 2013, the two countries signed a protocol on negotiations and cooperation between their foreign ministries.<ref name=\"Hotham\" /> In 2016, it was revealed that the Congolese government of [[Joseph Kabila]] had purchased pistols and hired military instructors from North Korea.<ref name=\"Ramani\" />\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Egypt}}\n|<!--Date started-->1963\n|See [[Egypt–North Korea relations]]{{pb}}North Korea and [[Egypt]] have a long history of good relations. Egypt recognized North Korea in 1963. It did not recognize South Korea until 1995. North Korea gave Egypt military aid during the 1973 [[Yom Kippur War]]. In the 1980s, Egyptian President [[Hosni Mubarak]] visited North Korea four times. Egyptian company [[Global Telecom Holding|Orascom]] helped create North Korea's cell phone network. As of September 12, 2017, Egypt announced it was suspending military ties with North Korea.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nknews.org/2011/03/the-egypt-dprk-relationship/|title=The Egypt–DPRK Relationship|last=Ducret|first=Julien|date=March 10, 2011|work=[[NK News]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160624015155/https://www.nknews.org/2011/03/the-egypt-dprk-relationship/|archive-date=June 24, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Equatorial Guinea}}\n|<!--Date started-->1969\n|See [[Equatorial Guinea–North Korea relations]]{{pb}}[[Equatorial Guinea]]'s first leader, [[Francisco Macías Nguema]], established close ties with North Korea in 1969. The relationship continued after his overthrow. In 2016, [[Kim Yong-nam]] of North Korea visited Equatorial Guinea and held amicable talks with President [[Teodoro Obiang Nguema Mbasogo|Teodoro Obiang]].<ref name=\"Ramani\" />{{pb}}North Korean companies publicly operated in Equatorial Guinea until 2017, when the host government said all workers has been \"asked to leave\" to comply with U.N. Sanctions. However, it is possible that workers remain present in a covert manner.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bone |first1=R. Maxwell |title=North Korea and Equatorial Guinea |url=https://thediplomat.com/2020/07/north-korea-and-equatorial-guinea/ |website=The Diplomat |access-date=July 16, 2020 |archive-date=July 13, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200713135304/https://thediplomat.com/2020/07/north-korea-and-equatorial-guinea/ |url-status=live }}</ref> \n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Ethiopia}}\n|<!--Date started-->\n|[[Ethiopia]] has had diplomatic relations with North Korea since the 1970s. North Korea has provided training for Ethiopian militias and special forces, and supplied munitions, tanks, Armoured Personnel Carriers, and artillery. It has also helped establish two arms factories. However, economic relations have become restricted by United Nations sanctions.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nknews.org/2017/08/ethiopia-working-to-restrict-north-korean-embassys-bank-accounts-mfa/|title=Ethiopia working to restrict North Korean embassy's bank accounts: MFA|last=Macdonald|first=Hamish|date=August 3, 2017|work=[[NK News]]|access-date=August 4, 2017|archive-date=August 5, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170805055740/https://www.nknews.org/2017/08/ethiopia-working-to-restrict-north-korean-embassys-bank-accounts-mfa/|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Gambia}}\n|<!--Date started-->1973\n|See [[Gambia–North Korea relations]]{{pb}}[[The Gambia]] and North Korea have had relations since 1973, with a diplomatic mission of North Korea opening in 1975.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Gambia and the World: A History of the Foreign Policy of Africa's Smallest State, 1965–1995|last=Touray|first=Omar A.|date=2000|publisher=[[German Institute of Global and Area Studies]]|isbn=978-392-804-966-5|location=[[Hamburg]]|page=71}}</ref> In later years, North Korea sent karate instructors to the country, and had varying strong bilateral relations between the two countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.statehouse.gm/NKorea-Pres-2day-working-visit_01-03_042010.htm|title=DPRK Presidium President Pays Maiden Visit to The Gambia|last=Ceesay|first=Alhagie|date=April 3, 2010|website=statehouse.gm|publisher=[[Politics of the Gambia|Government of the Gambia]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150109154354/http://www.statehouse.gm/NKorea-Pres-2day-working-visit_01-03_042010.htm|archive-date=January 9, 2015|url-status=dead|access-date=January 9, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://standard.gm/site/news/5676-Gambia-votes-against-referring-North-Korea-ICC.html|title=Gambia votes against referring North Korea to ICC|last=Darboe|first=Mustapha|date=December 24, 2014|newspaper=The Standard|access-date=January 9, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150109153052/http://standard.gm/site/news/5676-Gambia-votes-against-referring-North-Korea-ICC.html|archive-date=January 9, 2015|url-status=dead|location=[[Bakau]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.pri.org/stories/2015-01-06/gambia-worst-dictatorship-youve-probably-never-heard|title=The Gambia is the worst dictatorship you've probably never heard of|last=Porzucki|first=Nina|date=January 6, 2015|newspaper=[[Public Radio International]]|access-date=January 9, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150109044123/http://www.pri.org/stories/2015-01-06/gambia-worst-dictatorship-youve-probably-never-heard|archive-date=January 9, 2015|url-status=live|location=[[Minneapolis]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.modernghana.com/news/425325/1/the-gambia-the-case-of-a-north-korea-in-the-heart-.html|title=The Gambia: The case of a North Korea in the heart of West Africa|last=Jallow|first=Matthew K.|date=October 22, 2012|newspaper=Modern Ghana|access-date=January 9, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150109154717/http://www.modernghana.com/news/425325/1/the-gambia-the-case-of-a-north-korea-in-the-heart-.html|archive-date=January 9, 2015|url-status=live|location=[[Accra]]}}</ref> Hong Son Phy is currently the accredited ambassador to [[Banjul]].<ref name=\"DailyObserver\">{{cite news|url=http://observer.gm/africa/gambia/article/diplomat-says-nkorea-to-cooperate-with-gambia-on-agric-others|title=Diplomat says N/Korea to cooperate with Gambia on agric, others|last=Ndow|first=Musa|date=July 18, 2014|newspaper=Daily Observer|access-date=January 9, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150109154555/http://observer.gm/africa/gambia/article/diplomat-says-nkorea-to-cooperate-with-gambia-on-agric-others|archive-date=January 9, 2015|url-status=dead|location=[[Banjul]]}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Ghana}}\n|<!--Date started-->1964\n|See [[Ghana–North Korea relations]]{{pb}}[[Ghana]] and [[North Korea]] established [[diplomatic relations]] in 1964.{{sfn|Wertz|Oh|Kim|2016|p=3}}{{pb}}Even before diplomatic relations were established, Ghana had campaigned, along with other African nations, for recognition of North Korea as an observer in the UN.{{sfn|Armstrong|2013|p=223}} Trade relations between the two countries preceded diplomatic relations.{{sfn|Armstrong|2013|p=144}} [[Kim Il Sung]] shared much in common politically with Ghana's [[Kwame Nkrumah]].{{sfn|Schaefer|2009|p=119}} After Nkrumah was ousted,<ref name=\"Owusu-Ansah2014\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RBv2AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA240|title=Historical Dictionary of Ghana|last=Owusu-Ansah|first=David|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield Publishers|year=2014|isbn=978-0-8108-7500-5|edition=4th|location=London|page=240|access-date=June 21, 2018|archive-date=October 28, 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231028021038/https://books.google.com/books?id=RBv2AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA240#v=onepage&q&f=false|url-status=live}}</ref> North Korea ended up in a diplomatic spat with Ghana, which accused it of training anti-government rebels.<ref name=\"Facts\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uQ1yAAAAMAAJ|title=Some Facts about North Korea|publisher=Naewoe Press|year=1984|location=Seoul|page=38|oclc=603996576|access-date=June 21, 2018|archive-date=October 28, 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231028021043/https://books.google.com/books?id=uQ1yAAAAMAAJ|url-status=live}}</ref> By the late-1960s, North Korea was again supporting Ghana as an anti-imperialist force in Africa.<ref name=\"Cha2013\">{{cite book|title=The Impossible State: North Korea, Past and Future|last=Cha|first=Victor|publisher=Vintage|year=2013|isbn=978-0-099-57865-9|location=London|pages=47–48}}</ref> In the 1980s, Ghana's [[Provisional National Defence Council]] successfully sought aid from North Korea and other socialist countries in order to be more independent from Western powers.<ref name=\"Bobiash1992\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QCuwCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA93|title=South-South Aid: How Developing Countries Help Each Other|last=Bobiash|first=Donald|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan UK|year=1992|isbn=978-1-349-11623-2|page=93|access-date=June 21, 2018|archive-date=October 28, 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231028021006/https://books.google.com/books?id=QCuwCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA93#v=onepage&q&f=false|url-status=live}}</ref> An agreement on [[Cultural diplomacy|cultural exchange]] was signed for 1993–1995.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Fa26AAAAIAAJ|title=Vantage Point|publisher=Naewoe Press|year=1993|volume=16|location=Seoul|page=30|oclc=29800060|access-date=June 21, 2018|archive-date=October 28, 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231028021006/https://books.google.com/books?id=Fa26AAAAIAAJ|url-status=live}}</ref>{{pb}}There was a North Korean embassy in Ghana until it was closed down in 1998.{{sfn|Wertz|Oh|Kim|2016|p=6n20}} The current North Korean ambassador to Ghana is [[Kil Mun-yong]].<ref name=\"Publications2003\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jj4J-AXGDaQC&pg=PA494|title=Africa South of the Sahara 2004|publisher=Europa|year=2003|isbn=978-1-85743-183-4|location=London|page=494}}</ref>{{sfn|''North Korea Handbook''|2002|p=532}} Trade between the two countries consists mainly of North Korean exports of [[cement]] and Ghanaian cocoa, [[gemstones]], and [[pearls]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://issafrica.s3.amazonaws.com/site/uploads/research-report-dprk.pdf|title=Cooperation between African states and the Democratic People's Republic of Korea|last1=DuPre|first1=Annie|last2=Kasprzyk|first2=Nicolas|last3=Stot|first3=Noël|publisher=Institute for Security Studies|year=2016|page=32|access-date=October 6, 2017|archive-date=November 13, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171113092147/https://issafrica.s3.amazonaws.com/site/uploads/research-report-dprk.pdf|url-status=live}}</ref> There is a Korea–Ghana Friendship Association for cultural exchange.{{sfn|''North Korea Handbook''|2002|p=817}}\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Guinea-Bissau}}\n|<!--Date started-->\n|See [[Guinea-Bissau–North Korea relations]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Kenya}}\n|<!--Date started-->\n|See [[Kenya–North Korea relations]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Libya}}\n|<!--Date started-->\n|See [[Libya–North Korea relations]]{{pb}}In the 1970s and 1980s, the Libyan government led by Libyan leader [[Muammar Gaddafi]] established close ties with the North Korean government and purchased a significant amount of North Korea's weaponry.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nknews.org/2015/01/north-korea-and-libya-friendship-through-artillery/|title=North Korea and Libya: friendship through artillery|last1=Oliemans|first1=Joost|date=January 5, 2015|work=[[NK News]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160614122836/https://www.nknews.org/2015/01/north-korea-and-libya-friendship-through-artillery/|archive-date=June 14, 2016|url-status=dead|last2=Mitzer|first2=Stijn|access-date=June 8, 2016}}</ref> In 2015, it was estimated that 300 to 400 North Korean citizens were living in Libya.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Madagascar}}\n|<!--Date started-->\n|North Korea has been an ally of [[Madagascar]] since the 1970s. North Korea provided assistance in construction projects, such as building the [[Iavoloha Palace]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://calvertjournal.com/features/show/5336/red-africa-che-onejoon-north-korea-statues-africa|title=The Pyongyang connection: North Korea's strange and surprisingly effective charm offensive in Africa|last=Goff|first=Samuel|date=2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160825123722/http://calvertjournal.com/features/show/5336/red-africa-che-onejoon-north-korea-statues-africa|archive-date=August 25, 2016|url-status=live|publisher=The Calvert Journal}}</ref> In 1976, Madagascar hosted a conference on the ''[[Juche]]'' concept, an established part of North Korea's foreign policy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://countrystudies.us/madagascar/29.htm|title=Madagascar: Foreign Relations|publisher=US Library of Congress|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160409082613/http://countrystudies.us/madagascar/29.htm|archive-date=April 9, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Mauritania}}\n|<!--Date started-->1964\n|See [[Mauritania–North Korea relations]]{{pb}}North Korea and [[Mauritania]] established relations in 1964. President [[Moktar Ould Daddah]] visited Pyongyang in 1967, while Kim Il Sung went to Mauritania in 1975. Relations soured shortly afterwards when North Korea recognised the [[Sahrawi Arab Democratic Republic]]. In 2017, a North Korean delegation visited Mauritania, and the two governments pledged to increase co-operation.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nknews.org/2017/05/north-korean-delegation-visits-mauritania-amid-diplomatic-pressure|title=North Korean delegation visits Mauritania amid diplomatic pressure|last=Macdonald|first=Hamish|date=May 2, 2017|work=[[NK News]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170502234028/https://www.nknews.org/2017/05/north-korean-delegation-visits-mauritania-amid-diplomatic-pressure/|archive-date=May 2, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Mozambique}}\n|<!--Date started-->\n|[[Mozambique]] has a history of good relations with North Korea. Its capital Maputo has a street called Avenida Kim Il Sung after the founder of North Korea.<ref name=\"Sieff\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/africa/north-koreas-surprising-lucrative-relationship-with-africa/2017/07/10/c4e6f65d-30fe-4bd2-b178-d90daaac3007_story.html|title=North Korea's surprising, lucrative relationship with Africa|last=Sieff|first=Kevin|date=July 10, 2017|newspaper=Washington Post|access-date=July 10, 2017|archive-date=January 13, 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230113195159/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/africa/north-koreas-surprising-lucrative-relationship-with-africa/2017/07/10/c4e6f65d-30fe-4bd2-b178-d90daaac3007_story.html|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2016 a delegation of the [[Mozambique Liberation Front]] visited Pyongyang and met with members of the Workers' Party of Korea.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nkleadershipwatch.wordpress.com/2016/05/26/ri-su-yong-meets-with-mozambique-delegation/|title=Ri Su Yong Meets with Mozambique Delegation|date=May 26, 2016|publisher=North Korea Leadership Watch|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161013045141/https://nkleadershipwatch.wordpress.com/2016/05/26/ri-su-yong-meets-with-mozambique-delegation/|archive-date=October 13, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Namibia}}\n|<!--Date started-->\n|See [[Namibia–North Korea relations]]{{pb}}[[Namibia]]'s ruling party, the [[South West African People's Organisation]] (SWAPO) has had a longstanding historical relationship with North Korea, dating back to the [[South African Border War]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Liberating Namibia: The Long Diplomatic Struggle Between the United Nations and South Africa|last=Udogu|first=E. Ike|date=2011|publisher=[[McFarland & Company|McFarland]]|isbn=978-078-648-878-0|location=[[Jefferson, North Carolina|Jefferson]]|pages=123, 169}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=A History of Resistance in Namibia|last=Katjavivi|first=Peter H.|date=1988|publisher=[[James Currey|James Currey Publishers]]|isbn=978-085-255-320-6|location=[[Melton, Suffolk|Melton]]|page=86}}</ref><ref name=\"TonchiLindeke2012\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Mls4H1mnN_0C&pg=PA306|title=Historical Dictionary of Namibia|last1=Tonchi|first1=Victor L.|last2=Lindeke|first2=William A.|last3=Grotpeter|first3=John J.|date=August 31, 2012|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-0-8108-7990-4|edition=Second|location=Plymouth|page=306}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.foxnews.com/world/namibias-vote-on-nov-28-likely-to-follow-southern-african-pattern-_-victory-for-ruling-party|title=Namibia's vote on Nov. 28 likely to follow southern African pattern – victory for ruling party|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|date=November 23, 2014|newspaper=[[Fox News Channel|Fox News]]|access-date=December 26, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150127125426/http://www.foxnews.com/world/2014/11/23/namibia-vote-on-nov-28-likely-to-follow-southern-african-pattern-victory-for/|archive-date=January 27, 2015|url-status=live|location=[[New York City]]}}</ref> Beginning in 1964, North Korea provided training and arms to SWAPO's armed wing, the [[People's Liberation Army of Namibia]] (PLAN), which was engaged in an insurgency against the South African government.<ref name=\"DPRK\">{{cite book|title=Terrorism, the North Korean connection|last=Bermudez|first=Joseph|publisher=Crane, Russak & Company|year=1997|isbn=978-0844816104|location=New York|page=124}}</ref><ref name=\"Devils\">{{cite book|title=The Devils Are Among Us: The War for Namibia|last1=Herbstein|first1=Denis|last2=Evenson|first2=John|publisher=Zed Books Ltd|year=1989|isbn=978-0862328962|location=London|pages=14–23}}</ref> Following Namibian independence, North Korea established an embassy in Windhoek; however, the current status of the embassy remains unclear.<ref name=\"Grobler\">{{cite news|url=http://mg.co.za/article/2013-04-26-00-north-koreas-deals-in-nambia-a-mystery|title=North Korea's deals in Namibia a mystery|last=Grobler|first=John|date=April 26, 2013|newspaper=[[Mail & Guardian]]|access-date=December 26, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141226234628/http://mg.co.za/article/2013-04-26-00-north-koreas-deals-in-nambia-a-mystery|archive-date=December 26, 2014|url-status=live|location=[[Johannesburg]]}}</ref>{{pb}}[[Kim Yong-nam]], [[Chairman of the Presidium of the Supreme People's Assembly]], visited Namibia in 2008, and several bilateral agreements have been signed. North Korea has helped build state houses in the regions within the country, and military co-operation continues even with sanctions on North Korea.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://english.hani.co.kr/arti/english_edition/e_northkorea/277395.html|title=N. Korea, Namibia reach deals|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|date=March 22, 2008|newspaper=[[The Hankyoreh]]|access-date=December 26, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141227002338/http://english.hani.co.kr/arti/english_edition/e_northkorea/277395.html|archive-date=December 27, 2014|url-status=live|location=[[Seoul]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.namibian.com.na/indexx.php?archive_id=89598&page_type=archive_story_detail&page=1253|title=Namibia and North Korean relations to remain positive|last=Sasman|first=Catherine|date=December 20, 2011|newspaper=[[The Namibian]]|access-date=December 26, 2014|archive-url=https://archive.today/20141226233842/http://www.namibian.com.na/indexx.php?archive_id=89598&page_type=archive_story_detail&page=1253|archive-date=December 26, 2014|url-status=dead|location=[[Windhoek]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/africaandindianocean/namibia/9322603/Namibia-plans-mini-state-houses-for-President-Hifikepunye-Pohamba.html|title=Namibia plans 'mini state houses' for President Hifikepunye Pohamba|last=Laing|first=Aislinn|date=June 12, 2012|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|access-date=December 26, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141227075457/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/africaandindianocean/namibia/9322603/Namibia-plans-mini-state-houses-for-President-Hifikepunye-Pohamba.html|archive-date=December 27, 2014|url-status=live|location=[[Johannesburg]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nknews.org/2016/06/namibian-delegation-visits-n-korea-despite-sanctions-questions/|title=Namibian delegation visits N.Korea despite sanctions questions|last=O'Carroll|first=Chad|date=June 27, 2016|work=[[NK News]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160627034333/https://www.nknews.org/2016/06/namibian-delegation-visits-n-korea-despite-sanctions-questions/|archive-date=June 27, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=North Korea News|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|date=1994|publisher=Naewoe Press|page=12}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Nigeria}}\n|<!--Date started-->1976\n|See [[Nigeria-North Korea relations]]{{pb}}[[Nigeria]] and North Korea established diplomatic relations in 1976. In 2014, they signed an agreement to facilitate the exchange of information about technology, including exchanges and joint projects between universities. North Korea also proposed that Nigeria become a permanent member of the UN Security Council.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nknews.org/2014/05/north-korea-and-nigeria-sign-cooperation-agreement/|title=North Korea and Nigeria sign cooperation agreement|last=Byrne|first=Leo|date=May 7, 2014|work=[[NK News]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160604130545/http://www.nknews.org/2014/05/north-korea-and-nigeria-sign-cooperation-agreement/|archive-date=June 4, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Rwanda}}\n|<!--Date started-->\n|See [[North Korea–Rwanda relations]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Senegal}}\n|<!--Date started-->1972\n|[[Senegal]] and North Korea have had diplomatic relations since 1972.{{sfn|Wertz|Oh|Kim|2016|p=9}} The [[African Renaissance Monument]] in [[Dakar]], Senegal, was built by [[Mansudae Overseas Projects]], a company from North Korea.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/8435805.stm|title=Senegal President Wade apologises for Christ comments|date=December 31, 2009|work=[[BBC News]]|access-date=July 12, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141008064506/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/8435805.stm|archive-date=October 8, 2014|url-status=live|location=London}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Seychelles}}\n|<!--Date started-->\n|During the 1977–2004 rule of President [[France-Albert René]], the [[Socialism|socialist]] and non-aligned government of Seychelles maintained close relations with North Korea, receiving significant North Korean developmental aid.<ref>{{cite book|title=Social Policies in Seychelles|last1=Campling|first1=Liam|last2=Confiance|first2=Hansel|last3=Purvis|first3=Marie-Therese|date=2011|publisher=Commonwealth Secretariat|isbn=978-184-929-065-4|page=26}}<!--|access-date=25 December 2014 --></ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Somalia}}\n|<!--Date started--> 1967 (April 13)\n|See [[North Korea–Somalia relations]]{{pb}}Diplomatic relations between North Korea and [[Somalia]] were formally established on April 13, 1967. This late-1950s to 1960s period was when North Korea had first declared autonomous diplomacy.{{sfn|Wertz|Oh|Kim|2016|p=3}} However, to this day North Korea favours Ethiopia rather than Somalia during the Ethio-Somali conflict.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|South Africa}}\n|<!--Date started-->\n|See [[North Korea–South Africa relations]]{{pb}}North Korea supported the [[African National Congress]] in its struggle against [[apartheid]] in [[South Africa]]. North Korea campaigned against the white minority government and provided military training to ANC fighters in camps in [[Angola]]. In 1998, after the end of apartheid, North Korea and South Africa established diplomatic relations. A North Korean embassy was established in Pretoria. The two governments continue to have friendly relations.<ref name=\"Young\" />\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|South Sudan}}\n|<!--Date started-->\n|North Korea and [[South Sudan]] established diplomatic relations in November 2011, shortly after South Sudan gained independence from [[Sudan]].<ref>[http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/news/2011/11/18/74/0200000000AEN20111118009800315F.HTML N. Korea, South Sudan establish full diplomatic ties] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120526020843/http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/news/2011/11/18/74/0200000000AEN20111118009800315F.HTML|date=May 26, 2012}}, Yonhap News</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Tanzania}}\n|<!--Date started-->\n|See [[North Korea–Tanzania relations]]{{pb}}[[Tanzania]] and North Korea have a long history of military cooperation, going back to their mutual support for anti-imperialist struggle in southern Africa during the Cold War.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nknews.org/2013/08/tanzania-wont-deny-n-korea-is-providing-military-assistance/|title=Tanzania won't deny N. Korea is providing military assistance|last=Hotham|first=Oliver|date=August 15, 2013|work=[[NK News]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160624023206/https://www.nknews.org/2013/08/tanzania-wont-deny-n-korea-is-providing-military-assistance/|archive-date=June 24, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2016, there were 11 North Korean medical clinics operating in Tanzania, two others having recently been shut down by the government.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rfa.org/english/news/korea/tanzania-shutters-two-04192016143509.html|title=Tanzania Shutters Two North Korean Medical Clinics|date=April 19, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160420104841/http://www.rfa.org/english/news/korea/tanzania-shutters-two-04192016143509.html|archive-date=April 20, 2016|url-status=live|publisher=[[Radio Free Asia]]}}</ref> In 2017, it was reported that Tanzania was planning to open a general hospital employing dozens of North Korean doctors.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://m.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20170124000573#cb|title=Tanzania to import NK doctors due to manpower shortage|date=January 24, 2017|newspaper=[[The Korea Herald]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170203173540/http://m.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20170124000573|archive-date=February 3, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Togo}}\n|<!--Date started-->\n|See [[North Korea–Togo relations]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Uganda}}\n|<!--Date started-->\n|[[Uganda]] is a long-term ally of North Korea. [[Yoweri Museveni]], Uganda's president since 1986, has said that he learned basic Korean from [[Kim Il Sung]] during visits to North Korea.<ref name=\"Sieff\" /> North Korea has provided training for pilots, technicians, police, marine forces, and special forces. In 2016 Uganda stated that it was ending this co-operation due to United Nations sanctions against North Korea's nuclear weapons program. Uganda indicated, however, that it still considered North Korea to be a friend.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nknews.org/pro/uganda-reveals-another-military-contract-with-north-korea|title=Uganda reveals another military contract with North Korea|last=Macdonald|first=Hamish|date=July 20, 2016|work=[[NK News]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160721113500/https://www.nknews.org/pro/uganda-reveals-another-military-contract-with-north-korea/|archive-date=July 21, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nknews.org/2016/12/uganda-disengages-with-n-korea-in-areas-where-sanctions-apply/|title=Uganda disengages with N.Korea in \"areas where sanctions apply\"|last=O'Carroll|first=Chad|date=December 12, 2016|work=[[NK News]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161213110456/https://www.nknews.org/2016/12/uganda-disengages-with-n-korea-in-areas-where-sanctions-apply/|archive-date=December 13, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Following the imposition of strict [[Sanctions against North Korea]] in 2017, Uganda claimed to have cut all of its relations with the country. However, this was later proven to be false given the presence of North Koreans in Uganda. This was seen as evidence of the personal fondness Ugandan President [[Yoweri Museveni]] has of North Korea.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bone |first1=R. Maxwell |title=Uganda: North Korea's African Ally |url=https://thediplomat.com/2019/10/uganda-north-koreas-african-ally/ |website=The Diplomat |access-date=July 16, 2020 |archive-date=July 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200708134637/https://thediplomat.com/2019/10/uganda-north-koreas-african-ally/ |url-status=live }}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Zimbabwe}}\n|<!--Date started-->\n|The relationship between North Korea and [[Zimbabwe]] goes back to the struggle for independence. Soldiers of [[Robert Mugabe]]'s Zimbabwean African National Liberation Army were trained in North Korea in the 1970s.<ref name=\"Young\" /> In 1980, after independence was gained, the new Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe visited North Korea. In October 1980, Kim Il Sung and Mugabe signed an agreement for an exchange of soldiers. Following this agreement, 106 North Korean soldiers arrived in [[Zimbabwe]] to train a brigade of soldiers that became known as the [[Zimbabwean Fifth Brigade|Fifth Brigade]]. Zimbabwe's governing party, the [[ZANU-PF]], mourned the death of North Korean leader [[Kim Jong Il]] in 2011. In 2013, the two countries signed an agreement, exchanging Zimbabwean uranium for North Korean arms.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nknews.org/2013/10/zimbabwe-and-north-korea-uranium-elephants-and-a-massacre/|title=Zimbabwe and North Korea: Uranium, elephants, and a massacre|last=Young|first=Benjamin R|date=October 30, 2013|work=[[NK News]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160324092138/https://www.nknews.org/2013/10/zimbabwe-and-north-korea-uranium-elephants-and-a-massacre/|archive-date=March 24, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>{{pb}}In 2019, the state-owned ''[[The Herald (Zimbabwe)|Zimbabwe Herald]]'' said that, \"Kim Il Sung lives forever in the hearts of the African people as their great saviour, true friend and benevolent mentor\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.herald.co.zw/kim-il-sungs-contribution-to-africa/|title=Kim Il Sung's contribution to Africa|date=July 4, 2019|publisher=Herald (Zimbabwe)|access-date=August 8, 2019|archive-date=July 5, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190705084036/https://www.herald.co.zw/kim-il-sungs-contribution-to-africa/|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|}\n\n===Americas===\n{{See also|North Korea–Latin America relations}}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:100%; margin:auto;\"\n! style=\"width:15%;\" |Country\n! style=\"width:12%;\" |Formal Relations Began\n!Notes\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Argentina}}\n|<!--Date started-->June 1, 1973{{pb}}'''(suspended June 14, 1977)'''\n|See [[Argentina–North Korea relations]]{{pb}}Diplomatic relations between Argentina and North Korea were established on June 1, 1973. North Korea had an embassy in Buenos Aires from 1973 to 1977. On June 14, 1977, Argentina suspended diplomatic relations with North Korea.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Belize}}\n|<!--Date started-->June 20, 1991\n|Both countries established diplomatic relations on June 20, 1991.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.mfa.gov.bz/images/documents/DIPLOMATIC%20RELATIONS.pdf |title=Diplomatic Relations – Belize |access-date=February 23, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171230194831/http://www.mfa.gov.bz/images/documents/DIPLOMATIC%20RELATIONS.pdf |archive-date=December 30, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Brazil}}\n|<!--Date started-->\n|See [[Brazil–North Korea relations]]{{pb}}Despite the Brazilian government's economic relations with North Korea, it has generally condemned controversial North Korean actions that threaten stability in East Asia, such as the 2009 North Korean nuclear test, upon which the Brazilian Ministry for Foreign Affairs stated that the Brazilian Government vehemently condemns North Korea's nuclear test and urged the country to sign the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty and return to the six-party talks as soon as possible, and the ROKS Cheonan sinking, upon which the Brazilian Ministry of External Relations issued a statement saying the government expresses solidarity with South Korea and urged stability on the Korean peninsula.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Canada}}\n|<!--Date started-->2001{{pb}}'''(suspended May 25, 2010)'''\n|See [[Canada–North Korea relations]]{{pb}}Diplomatic relations between Canada and North Korea were established in February 2001. However, there are no official embassies between the two nations. Canada is represented by the Canadian Ambassador resident in Seoul, and North Korea is represented by their position in the United Nations. On May 25, 2010, Canada suspended diplomatic relations with North Korea.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite news |url=http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/canada/breakingnews/canada-suspends-diplomatic-relations-with-north-korea-over-warship-sinking-94869569.html |title= Canada suspends diplomatic relations with North Korea over warship sinking - Winnipeg Free Press|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100531040130/http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/canada/breakingnews/canada-suspends-diplomatic-relations-with-north-korea-over-warship-sinking-94869569.html |archive-date=May 31, 2010}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Cuba}}\n|<!--Date started-->1960\n|See [[Cuba–North Korea relations]]{{pb}}North Korea has had diplomatic relations with Cuba since 1960 and maintains an embassy in Havana. Cuba has been one of North Korea's most consistent allies.<ref name=\"thediplomat.com\">{{cite magazine|last=Ramani|first=Samuel|date=June 7, 2016|title=The North Korea-Cuba Connection|url=https://thediplomat.com/2016/06/the-north-korea-cuba-connection/|url-status=live|magazine=The Diplomat|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160608150617/https://thediplomat.com/2016/06/the-north-korea-cuba-connection/|archive-date=June 8, 2016}}</ref> North Korea media portrays Cubans as comrades in the common cause of socialism.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://kcnawatch.co/newstream/1472305652-347575089/dprk-cuba-relations-showcase-mutual-support-and-solidarity/|title=DPRK-Cuba relations showcase mutual support and solidarity|date=August 27, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160828222245/https://kcnawatch.co/newstream/1472305652-347575089/dprk-cuba-relations-showcase-mutual-support-and-solidarity/|archive-date=August 28, 2016|url-status=live|work=[[The Pyongyang Times]]}}</ref>{{pb}}During the Cold War, North Korea and Cuba forged a bond of solidarity based on their militant positions opposing American power. In 1968, [[Raúl Castro]] stated their views were \"completely identical on everything\".<ref name=\"nknews.org\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nknews.org/2016/11/revolutionary-solidarity-castros-cozy-relationship-with-north-korea/|title=Revolutionary Solidarity: Castro's cozy relationship with North Korea|last=Young|first=Benjamin R|date=August 28, 2016|work=[[NK News]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161221060457/https://www.nknews.org/2016/11/revolutionary-solidarity-castros-cozy-relationship-with-north-korea/|archive-date=December 21, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Che Guevara]], then a Cuban government minister, visited North Korea in 1960, and proclaimed it a model for Cuba to follow.<ref>{{cite book|title=Korea's Place in the Sun: A Modern History|last=Cumings|first=Bruce|publisher=[[W. W. Norton & Company]]|year=2005|isbn=978-0-393-32702-1|location=New York|page=394|author-link=Bruce Cumings}}</ref> Cuban leader [[Fidel Castro]] visited in 1986.<ref name=\"ThreeDay\">{{cite news|url=http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/news/2016/11/28/0200000000AEN20161128002852315.html|title=N.K. declares 3-day mourning over ex-Cuban leader Castro's death|date=November 28, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161128200044/http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/news/2016/11/28/0200000000AEN20161128002852315.html|archive-date=November 28, 2016|url-status=live|publisher=[[Yonhap News Agency]]}}</ref> Cuba was one of the few countries that showed solidarity with North Korea by boycotting the [[Seoul Olympics]] in 1988.<ref name=\"nknews.org\" />{{pb}}In 2016, the [[Workers' Party of Korea]] and the [[Communist Party of Cuba]] met to discuss strengthening ties.<ref name=\"thediplomat.com\" /> After Fidel Castro's death in 2016, North Korea government declared a three-day mourning period and sent an official delegation to his funeral.<ref name=\"ThreeDay\" /> Supreme Leader Kim Jong Un visited the Cuban embassy in Pyongyang to pay his respects.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2016-11/29/c_135866688.htm|title=DPRK leader conveys condolences over passing of Fidel Castro|date=November 29, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161129150803/http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2016-11/29/c_135866688.htm|archive-date=November 29, 2016|url-status=dead|publisher=Xinhua}}</ref>{{pb}}In 2018, the new Cuban President [[Miguel Díaz-Canel]] visited North Korea, stressing socialist solidarity and opposition to sanctions.<ref>{{cite magazine|date=November 4, 2018|title=Cuban President Meets North Korea's Kim Jong Un as Part of First Overseas Tour|url=http://time.com/5444537/cuba-north-korea-rusia-china/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181108233344/http://time.com/5444537/cuba-north-korea-rusia-china/|url-status=dead|archive-date=November 8, 2018|magazine=Time|accessdate=November 7, 2018}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Grenada}}\n|<!--Date started-->\n|See [[Grenada–North Korea relations]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Mexico}}\n|<!--Date started-->September 4, 1980\n| See [[Mexico–North Korea relations]]{{pb}}Both nations established diplomatic relations on September 4, 1980.\n* Mexico is accredited to North Korea from its embassy in [[Seoul]], [[South Korea]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://embamex.sre.gob.mx/corea/|title=Inicio|website=embamex.sre.gob.mx|access-date=September 4, 2017|archive-date=October 1, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201001050407/https://embamex.sre.gob.mx/corea/|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* North Korea has an embassy in [[Mexico City]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://acreditadas.sre.gob.mx/|title=Representaciones Diplomáticas Acreditadas en México|website=acreditadas.sre.gob.mx|access-date=September 4, 2017|archive-date=July 2, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180702204936/https://acreditadas.sre.gob.mx/|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* On September 7, 2017, Mexico expelled its North Korean ambassador as punishment for Pyongyang's nuclear tests in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/world/mexico-americas/la-fg-mexico-north-korea-20170907-story.html|title=Mexico expels North Korean ambassador over nuclear tests|last=Linthicum|first=Kate|website=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=September 8, 2017|access-date=February 20, 2020|archive-date=June 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200624191536/https://www.latimes.com/world/mexico-americas/la-fg-mexico-north-korea-20170907-story.html|url-status=live}}</ref> However, ties between the two countries have not yet been officially broken.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/09/08/mexico-expels-north-korean-ambassador-over-nuclear-tests.html|title=Mexico expels North Korean ambassador over nuclear tests|last=CNBC|website=[[CNBC]]|date=September 8, 2017|access-date=September 13, 2017|archive-date=September 14, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170914035322/https://www.cnbc.com/2017/09/08/mexico-expels-north-korean-ambassador-over-nuclear-tests.html|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Nicaragua}}\n|<!--Date started-->1979\n| North Korea gave military assistance to the [[Sandinista]] movement in the 1970s and 1980s. Nicaragua established relations with North Korea when the Sandinistas took power in 1979. Nicaraguan president [[Daniel Ortega]] visited North Korea in 1983 and 1986. 1988 Nicaragua showed its support for North Korea by boycotting the Seoul Olympics. Close relations ceased when the Sandinistas were voted out of office in 1990. In May 2007, after Ortega had been voted back into office, diplomatic ties were restored.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nknews.org/2021/11/why-the-sandinistas-sent-kim-il-sung-a-stuffed-crocodile-carrying-drinks/|title=Why the Sandinistas sent Kim Il Sung a stuffed crocodile carrying drinks|first=Benjamin|last=Young|publisher=[[NK News]]|date=November 8, 2021|access-date=November 10, 2021|archive-date=November 10, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211110000113/https://www.nknews.org/2021/11/why-the-sandinistas-sent-kim-il-sung-a-stuffed-crocodile-carrying-drinks/|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Peru}}\n|<!--Date started-->1988\n| See [[North Korea–Peru relations]]{{pb}}North Korea and Peru established diplomatic relations in 1988. North Korea supplied the Peruvian government with rifles to combat the [[Internal conflict in Peru|Shining Path insurgency]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1988/03/23/Peru-orders-weapons-from-North-Korea/1562575096400/|title=Peru orders weapons from North Korea|website=UPI|access-date=April 1, 2020|archive-date=April 6, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210406014837/https://www.upi.com/Archives/1988/03/23/Peru-orders-weapons-from-North-Korea/1562575096400/|url-status=live}}</ref> Even so, the Peruvian government condemned the third nuclear test by North Korea in 2013, saying \"the government of Peru calls on the government of North Korea to immediately stop these types of actions.\"<ref>Manuel Vigo, ''[http://www.peruthisweek.com/news-peru-government-condemns-north-koreas-third-nuclear-test-13593 Peru government condemns North Korea's third nuclear test]{{dead link|date=April 2018|bot=InternetArchiveBot|fix-attempted=yes}}'', Living in Peru, February 14, 2013.</ref> In September 2017, Peru expelled North Korean ambassadors from the country.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hankookilbo.com/v/1e749b34740948208992097bdb7cc734 |publisher=[[Hankook Ilbo]] |language=ko-kr |script-title=ko:페루도 북한 대사 추방 \"5일 안에 떠나라\" |date=September 12, 2017 |access-date=September 13, 2017 |archive-date=September 13, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170913183312/http://www.hankookilbo.com/v/1e749b34740948208992097bdb7cc734 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|United States}}\n|<!--Date started-->\n| See [[North Korea–United States relations]]{{pb}}Relations between the two countries developed primarily in the shadow of the [[Korean War]], and in recent years have been largely defined by North Korea's six tests of [[North Korea and weapons of mass destruction|nuclear weapons, its development of long-range missiles capable of striking targets thousands of miles away]], and its ongoing threats to strike the [[United States]][https://www.inquisitr.com/north-korea-issues-chilling-warning-to-donald-trump-threatens-to-wipe-out-us-military]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2013/04/12/world/asia/north-korea-questions.html?_r=0|title=In Focus: North Korea's Nuclear Threats|date=April 16, 2013|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=April 16, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130416011036/http://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2013/04/12/world/asia/north-korea-questions.html?_r=0|archive-date=April 16, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[South Korea]] with nuclear weapons and conventional forces.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/04/15/world/asia/north-korea-ultimatum/index.html|title=North Korea threatens to strike without warning|date=April 15, 2013|work=CNN|access-date=April 16, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130415213125/http://www.cnn.com/2013/04/15/world/asia/north-korea-ultimatum/index.html|archive-date=April 15, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-nkorea-threat-idUSBRE91I0J520130219|title=North Korea threatens South with 'final destruction'|date=February 19, 2013|work=Reuters|access-date=April 16, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130411013109/http://www.reuters.com/article/2013/02/19/us-nkorea-threat-idUSBRE91I0J520130219|archive-date=April 11, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>{{pb}}Trump met with Kim in Singapore on June 12, 2018. An agreement was signed between the two countries endorsing the 2017 Panmunjom Declaration signed by North and South Korea to work towards completely denuclearizing the Korean Peninsula.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/06/12/full-text-of-the-trump-kim-summit-agreement.html|title=Read the full text of the Trump-Kim agreement here|last=Rosenfeld|first=Everett|date=June 12, 2018|work=CNBC|access-date=October 2, 2018|archive-date=June 13, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180613013354/https://www.cnbc.com/2018/06/12/full-text-of-the-trump-kim-summit-agreement.html|url-status=live}}</ref> Following this,  [[2019 North Korea–United States Hanoi Summit|they met in Hanoi]] on February 27–28, 2019, but failed to achieve an agreement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/02/28/white-house-trump-kim-meetings-change-of-schedule.html|title=Trump-Kim summit was cut short after North Korea demanded an end to all sanctions|last=Rosenfeld|first=Everett|date=February 28, 2019|publisher=CNBC|access-date=February 28, 2019|archive-date=February 28, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190228095036/https://www.cnbc.com/2019/02/28/white-house-trump-kim-meetings-change-of-schedule.html|url-status=live}}</ref> On June 30, 2019, Trump met with Kim along with [[Moon Jae-in]] at the Korean DMZ.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://eu.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2019/06/29/donald-trump-looks-brief-handshake-meeting-kim-jong-un/1608092001/|title=Donald Trump meets Kim Jong Un in DMZ; steps onto North Korean soil|work=USA Today|date=June 30, 2019|access-date=October 17, 2019|archive-date=February 15, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210215213632/https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2019/06/29/donald-trump-looks-brief-handshake-meeting-kim-jong-un/1608092001/|url-status=live}}</ref> Talks in Stockholm began in October between US and North Korean negotiating teams, but broke down after one day.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://time.com/5693526/north-korea-us-nuclear-diplomacy-sweden/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191005155025/https://time.com/5693526/north-korea-us-nuclear-diplomacy-sweden/|url-status=dead|archive-date=October 5, 2019|title=North Korea Says Nuclear Talks Break Down While U.S. Says They Were 'Good'|first1=Jari|last1=Tanner|first2=Matthew|last2=Lee|magazine=Time|date=October 5, 2019|accessdate=September 21, 2020}}</ref>{{pb}}Sweden acts as the protecting power of United States interests in North Korea for consular matters.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Venezuela}}\n|1965\n|The two countries have had a friendly relationship since [[Hugo Chávez]] took power. In 2015, North Korea reopened its embassy in La Mercedes, Caracas, as solidarity between Caracas and Pyongyang has strengthened. The two countries also signed a bilateral agreement to build a giant statue.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.caracaschronicles.com/2015/06/23/guess-which-country-has-a-new-home-in-caracas/|title=Guess which country has a new home in Caracas?|first=Gustavo Hernández|last=A|date=June 23, 2015|access-date=May 26, 2018|archive-date=May 26, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180526112851/https://www.caracaschronicles.com/2015/06/23/guess-which-country-has-a-new-home-in-caracas/|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|}\n\n===Asia===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:100%; margin:auto;\"\n! style=\"width:15%;\" |Country\n! style=\"width:12%;\" |Formal Relations Began\n!Notes\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Armenia}}\n|<!--Date started-->1992\n|The establishment of diplomatic relations between [[Armenia]] and North Korea started in 1992 upon Armenia's independence from the USSR, but never progressed due to Armenia's protest of [[Human rights in North Korea|North Korea's numerous human rights violations]], nuclear weapons program, and its harsh treatment of the North Korean populace.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mfa.am/en/bilateral-relations/kp|title=Democratic People's Republic of Korea - Bilateral Relations|website=www.mfa.am|access-date=May 10, 2022|archive-date=May 28, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220528003933/https://www.mfa.am/en/bilateral-relations/kp|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Bangladesh}}\n|<!--Date started-->1971\n|See [[Bangladesh–North Korea relations]]{{pb}}[[Bangladesh]] currently operates a North Korean office through its embassy in [[Beijing, China]]. North Korea also formerly maintained an [[Embassy of North Korea, Dhaka|embassy]] in [[Dhaka]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nknews.org/pro/nk_directory/embassy-of-north-korea-in-dhaka-bangladesh/|title=North Korea Professional Research Platform|access-date=July 12, 2019|archive-date=July 12, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190712135356/https://www.nknews.org/pro/nk_directory/embassy-of-north-korea-in-dhaka-bangladesh/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nknews.org/2023/11/north-korea-closes-embassy-in-bangladesh-citing-operational-realignment/|title=North Korea closes embassy in Bangladesh, citing 'operational' realignment|date=November 27, 2023 |access-date=September 29, 2024}}</ref> Relations were strained during the 1971 [[Bangladesh Liberation War|Bangladesh War of Independence]] when North Korea supported the [[Government of East Pakistan]] and the [[Pakistan Armed Forces]].\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Cambodia}}\n|<!--Date started-->\n|See [[Cambodia–North Korea relations]]{{pb}}[[Cambodia]] and North Korea generally had good relations. When the [[Khmer Rouge]] was removed by a Vietnamese invasion in 1979, North Korea supported [[Norodom Sihanouk]] in an [[Coalition Government of Democratic Kampuchea|exile government]], and he lived in North Korea until 1991 when he became [[King of Cambodia]] and returned to the country with a bodyguard of individuals from North Korea.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Strangio|first=Sebastian|date=August 14, 2011|title=North Korea's New Friend?|url=https://thediplomat.com/2011/08/north-koreas-new-friend/|url-status=live|magazine=The Diplomat|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160807075025/https://thediplomat.com/2011/08/north-koreas-new-friend/|archive-date=August 7, 2016}}</ref> North Korea has an embassy in [[Phnom Penh]] and Cambodia has an embassy in [[Pyongyang]]. While North Korea has built the Angkor Panorama museum within the country, reportedly relations are strained with some saying that Cambodia could cast off North Korea as a partner although this seems unlikely since North Korea has asked for help from the country in reducing tensions on the [[Korean Peninsula]].<ref>Go Cambodia, \"[http://gocambodia.info/north-korea-seeks-cambodias-help/ North Korea seeks Cambodia's help]{{Dead link|date=January 2019|bot=InternetArchiveBot|fix-attempted=yes}}\", 2017.</ref><ref>Jack Board, ''[http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/asiapacific/the-curious-case-of-north-korea-in-cambodia-8767256 The curious case of North Korea in Cambodia] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170531193712/http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/asiapacific/the-curious-case-of-north-korea-in-cambodia-8767256|date=May 31, 2017}}'', [[Channel News Asia]], April 23, 2017.</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|last=Hunt|first=Lake|date=March 21, 2017|title=North Korea-Cambodia Relations: The Sound of Silence|url=https://thediplomat.com/2017/03/north-korea-cambodia-relations-the-sound-of-silence/|url-status=live|magazine=The Diplomat|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170411135940/https://thediplomat.com/2017/03/north-korea-cambodia-relations-the-sound-of-silence/|archive-date=April 11, 2017}}</ref>{{pb}}In 2016, one [[United Nations]] expert claimed that the [[Supreme Court of Cambodia]] upholding \"a life sentence for two top cadres of the 1970s Khmer Rouge found guilty of crimes against humanity\" will send a \"message\" to the leaders of North Korea even though the said country never supported the [[Khmer Rouge]].<ref>Prak Chan Thul, [https://www.reuters.com/article/us-cambodia-rouge-idUSKBN13I0DG Jailing of Khmer Rouge leaders 'sends message to North Korea': U.N. envoy] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170704231144/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-cambodia-rouge-idUSKBN13I0DG |date=July 4, 2017 }}, [[Reuters]], November 23, 2016.</ref> More directly, North Korea has defended Cambodia, saying in later 2016 that a division of the [[Office of the High Commissioner for Human Rights]] was operating illegally in the country, saying its operation violated the \"principle of respect for sovereignty and non-interference in domestic affairs\" and that \"every year the U.N. raises the issue of human rights while violating the principle of fairness when discussing human rights and showing sympathy for hostile acts against sovereign states.\"<ref>Elizabeth Shim, [http://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2016/11/10/North-Korea-intervenes-in-Cambodia-UN-human-rights-dispute/9301478806368/ North Korea intervenes in Cambodia, U.N. human rights dispute] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220065554/http://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2016/11/10/North-Korea-intervenes-in-Cambodia-UN-human-rights-dispute/9301478806368/|date=December 20, 2016}}, [[UPI]], November 10, 2016.</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|China}} (PRC)\n|<!--Date started-->October 6, 1949\n|See [[China–North Korea relations]] [[File:Sino-Korean Friendship Bridge across the Yalu.jpg|thumb|right|The [[Sino–Korean Friendship Bridge]] across the Yalu (Amnokgang) at [[Sinuiju]] and [[Dandong]]]]{{pb}}The People's Republic of China is often considered to be North Korea's closest ally.<ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Nanto|first1=Dick K.|last2=Manyin|first2=Mark E.|date=2011|title=China-North Korea Relations|url=https://digital.library.unt.edu/ark:/67531/metadc227656/|journal=North Korean Review|volume=7|issue=2|pages=94–101|doi=10.3172/NKR.7.2.94|issn=1551-2789|jstor=43908855|access-date=August 20, 2019|archive-date=August 19, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190819104445/https://digital.library.unt.edu/ark:/67531/metadc227656/|url-status=live|doi-access=free}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/chinas-xi-to-visit-north-korea-as-both-countries-lock-horns-with-united-states/2019/06/17/4777087c-90f5-11e9-b72d-d56510fa753e_story.html|title=China's Xi to visit North Korea as both countries lock horns with United States|first1=Gerry|last1=Shih|first2=Simon|last2=Denyer|date=June 17, 2019|newspaper=Washington Post|access-date=August 20, 2019|archive-date=July 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190725085044/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/chinas-xi-to-visit-north-korea-as-both-countries-lock-horns-with-united-states/2019/06/17/4777087c-90f5-11e9-b72d-d56510fa753e_story.html|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-48714872|title=N Korea hails 'invincible' relationship with China|date=June 21, 2019|access-date=July 25, 2019|language=en-GB|archive-date=August 6, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190806170632/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-48714872|url-status=live}}</ref> North Korea is also the only country with which China has a legally binding [[Sino-North Korean Mutual Aid and Cooperation Friendship Treaty|mutual aid and co-operation treaty]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-41152824|title=How much leverage does China have over North Korea?|last=Brown|first=Prof Kerry|date=September 5, 2017|access-date=August 2, 2019|language=en-GB|archive-date=July 6, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190706002440/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-41152824|url-status=live}}</ref>{{pb}}China and North Korea share a [[China–North Korea border|1,416-kilometre long border]] (890 miles) that corresponds to the course of the [[Yalu River|Yalu]] and [[Tumen river]]s, which both flow from Heaven Lake on [[Mount Paektu]]. The countries have six border crossings between them.<ref>Foley, James. \"China Steps Up Security on North Korean Border\", ''Jane's Intelligence Review'', November 1, 2003.</ref>{{pb}}The two countries are generally perceived to be on friendly terms; however, in recent years, both the relationship and friendliness between the two nations have gradually declined due to growing concern in the PRC over issues such as North Korea's [[North Korea and weapons of mass destruction#Nuclear weapons|nuclear weapons program]], [[ROKS Cheonan sinking|sinking of the ROKS ''Cheonan'']] and their [[bombardment of Yeonpyeong]]. After North Korea conducted [[2006 North Korean nuclear test|its first nuclear test]] in 2006, the Chinese government stated that they were \"resolutely opposed to it\" and voted for United Nations [[sanctions against North Korea]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2006-10/09/content_5180203.htm|title=China resolutely opposes DPRK's nuclear test|publisher=Xinhua News Agency|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090706072227/http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2006-10/09/content_5180203.htm|archive-date=July 6, 2009|url-status=dead|access-date=December 1, 2010}}</ref>{{pb}}The [[Council on Foreign Relations]] suggests that the China's main priority in its bilateral relations with North Korea is to prevent the collapse of [[Kim Jong Un]]'s government, concerned that such an event would provoke a surge of North Korean refugees into China. All the while Chinese counterparts are interested in a buffer zone to US-allied South Korea,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://seoul.usembassy.gov/rok_040209.html|title=President Obama Vows Strengthened U.S.-South Korea Ties|date=April 2, 2009|publisher=[[Embassy of the United States, Seoul]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090704211009/http://seoul.usembassy.gov/rok_040209.html|archive-date=July 4, 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref> it also suggests, however, that Chinese-North Korea relations may be soured due to China's concerns about [[Japan]]'s [[Military of Japan|remilitarization]] in response to North Korea's military behaviour.<ref name=\"cfr.org\" />{{pb}}The PRC permitted the [[Yanbian Korean Autonomous Prefecture|Yanbian Korean Ethnic Group Autonomous Prefecture]] to conduct border trade with North Korea in August 1954. In the 1950s, border trade between China and North Korea reached as high as 7.56 million Chinese renminbi. Trade was suspended due to the [[Cultural Revolution]] until a new contract was signed in 1982 between China and North Korea, which set the [[Swiss franc]] as the exchange currency. Since then, China-North Korea border trade has increased rapidly with the trade between [[Jilin Province]] and North Korea alone reaching 1.03 million Swiss francs (510K USD).<ref name=\"fx.sauder.ubc.ca\">[http://fx.sauder.ubc.ca/etc/USDpages.pdf \"Foreign Currency Units Per 1 U.S. Dollar, 1948–2007\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150512095429/http://fx.sauder.ubc.ca/etc/USDpages.pdf|date=May 12, 2015}}, Werner Antweiler, University of British Columbia, 2007.</ref> Trade volume amounted to 11.99 million Swiss francs (CHF) in 1983 (5.71M USD), CHF 100 million in 1985 (40.70M USD), CHF 160 million in 1988 (109.34M USD), and CHF 150 million (88.2M USD) in 1990.<ref name=\"fx.sauder.ubc.ca\" />{{pb}}The PRC is North Korea's largest trade partner, while North Korea ranked 82nd (in 2009) in China's trade partners. China provides about half of all North Korea's imports and received a quarter of its exports. The PRC's major imports from North Korea includes [[mineral]] fuels (coal), [[ore]]s, [[woven]] apparel, iron and steel, fish and seafood, and stone. North Korea's imports from mainland China include mineral fuels and oil, machinery, electrical machinery, vehicles, [[plastic]], and iron and steel. The PRC is a major source for North Korea imports of petroleum.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-39702554|title=Why are petrol prices spiking in N Korea?|last=Evans|first=Stephen|date=April 25, 2017|work=[[BBC News]]|access-date=April 25, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170425104002/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-39702554|archive-date=April 25, 2017|url-status=live|language=en-GB}}</ref> In 2009, exports to North Korea of mineral fuel oil totaled $327 million and accounted for 17% of all Chinese exports to North Korea. Much of China's trade with North Korea goes through the port of [[Dandong]] on the Yalu River.<ref>Lee, Chang-hak. \"China's Trade with N.K. Via Dandong Exceeds US $200 million.\" KOTRA, February 21, 2003</ref>{{pb}}During the Korean War from 1950 to 1953, China assisted North Korea, sending as many as 500,000 soldiers to support North Korean forces. In 1975, Kim Il Sung visited Beijing in a failed attempt to solicit support from China for a military invasion of South Korea.<ref>[https://www.wilsoncenter.org/publication/east-german-documents-kim-il-sungs-april-1975-trip-to-beijing \"East German Documents on Kim Il Sung's April 1975 Trip to Beijing\"] , NKIDP e-Dossier No. 7, May 2012</ref> On November 23, 2009, PRC Defence Minister [[Liang Guanglie]] visited Pyongyang, the first defense chief to visit since 2006.<ref>Associated Press, \"China's Defense Minister Travels to North Korea\", ''The China Post'', November 23, 2009</ref>{{pb}}In 2019, Chinese President and General Secretary of the Communist Party [[Xi Jinping]] visited North Korea, the first for a Chinese [[paramount leader]] in 14 years. This has been widely considered by observers as the improvement of relations between the two countries. Before his visit, Xi reaffirmed North Korea on ''[[Rodong Sinmun]]'' that China would support them \"no matter how the international situation changes\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/diplomacy/article/3015159/chinese-president-xi-jinping-gives-north-korean-leader-kim|title=Xi Jinping pledges support for Kim Jong-un and North Korea|date=June 19, 2019|website=South China Morning Post|language=en|access-date=August 19, 2019|archive-date=August 19, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190819103911/https://www.scmp.com/news/china/diplomacy/article/3015159/chinese-president-xi-jinping-gives-north-korean-leader-kim|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|''{{flag|Hong Kong}}''\n|<!--Date started-->1997\n|See [[Hong Kong–North Korea relations]]{{pb}}[[Hong Kong]] and North Korea have had official relations established since 1997, after the [[transfer of sovereignty over Hong Kong]] from the United Kingdom to the People's Republic of China.<ref>[https://www.scmp.com/article/325411/north-koreas-macau-based-trading-venture-opens-its-doors-deny-reports-espionage-and North Korea's Macau-based trading venture opens its doors to deny reports of espionage and shady deals] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160426073800/http://www.scmp.com/article/325411/north-koreas-macau-based-trading-venture-opens-its-doors-deny-reports-espionage-and|date=April 26, 2016}}, ''[[South China Morning Post]]'', September 3, 2000</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|India}}\n|<!--Date started-->\n|See [[India–North Korea relations]]{{pb}}India and North Korea have growing trade and diplomatic relations. India maintains a fully functioning embassy in Pyongyang and North Korea has an embassy in [[New Delhi]]. India has said that it wants the \"reunification\" of Korea.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mea.gov.in/mystart.php?id=50049826|title=Sorry for the inconvenience.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120405025720/http://www.mea.gov.in/mystart.php?id=50049826|archive-date=April 5, 2012|url-status=dead|access-date=February 19, 2015}}</ref> Many North Korean nationals receive training in India including in the fields of IT and science and technology. India has a bilateral trade of around half a billion dollars with North Korea. Also, India is increasingly being asked by the US to mediate in the Korean peninsula due to its strengthening relations with both North Korea and South Korea.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndtv.com/article/india/kims-death-will-india-north-korea-ties-improve-159218?pfrom=home-otherstories|title=Kim's death: Will India-North Korea ties improve?|work=NDTV.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120228205815/http://www.ndtv.com/article/india/kims-death-will-india-north-korea-ties-improve-159218?pfrom=home-otherstories|archive-date=February 28, 2012|url-status=live|access-date=February 19, 2015}}</ref>{{pb}}India voted in favour of Security Council resolutions [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 82|82]] and [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 83|83]] relating to the Korean War. However, India did not support [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 84|resolution 84]] for military assistance to South Korea. As a non-aligned country, India declined to fight against North Korea. Instead, India decided to send a medical unit to Korea as a humanitarian gesture. The 60th Indian Field Ambulance Unit, a unit of the [[Parachute Regiment (India)|Indian Airborne Division]], was selected to be dispatched to Korea. The unit consisted of 346-men including 14 doctors.<ref>Kim Chan Wahn. \"The Role of India in the Korean War\", ''[[International Area Studies Review]]'', June 2010; vol. 13(2), pp. 21–37</ref>{{pb}}After the Korean War, India again played an important role as the chair of the Neutral Nations Repatriation Commission in the Korean peninsula. India established consular relations with North Korea in 1962 and in 1973, established full diplomatic relations with it.<ref name=\"telegraphindia\">{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1111220/jsp/frontpage/story_14904670.jsp#.UNRYGuQ3vFY|title=The food bridge India built with Kim's Korea|last=Nayar|first=K.P.|date=December 20, 2011|newspaper=The Telegraph|access-date=December 21, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130330061819/http://www.telegraphindia.com/1111220/jsp/frontpage/story_14904670.jsp|archive-date=March 30, 2013|url-status=dead|location=Calcutta, India}}</ref> India's relationship with North Korea has however been affected by North Korea's relations with Pakistan especially due to its help for Pakistan's nuclear missile program. In 1999, India impounded a North Korean ship off the Kandla coast that was found to be carrying missile components and blueprints. India's relations with South Korea have far greater economic and technological depth and India's keenness for South Korean investments and technology have in turn affected the North's relations with India. India has consistently voiced its opposition to North Korea's nuclear and missile tests.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ndtv.com/article/india/kim-s-death-will-india-north-korea-ties-improve-159218|title=Kim's death: Will India-North Korea ties improve?|date=December 19, 2011|newspaper=NDTV|access-date=December 21, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130316045517/http://www.ndtv.com/article/india/kim-s-death-will-india-north-korea-ties-improve-159218|archive-date=March 16, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"thehindu\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/international/north-koreas-rocket-launch-unwarranted-india/article4192813.ece|title=North Korea's rocket launch unwarranted: India|last=Dikshit|first=Sandeep|date=December 13, 2012|newspaper=The Hindu|access-date=December 21, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121216044601/http://www.thehindu.com/news/international/north-koreas-rocket-launch-unwarranted-india/article4192813.ece|archive-date=December 16, 2012|url-status=live|location=Chennai, India}}</ref>{{pb}}Trade between India and North Korea has seen a large increase in recent years. From an average total trade of barely $100 million in the middle of the 2000s, it shot up to over $1 billion in 2009. The trade is overwhelmingly in India's favour, with its exports accounting for roughly $1 billion while North Korea's exports to India were worth $57 million. India's primary export to North Korea is refined petroleum products while silver and auto parts are the main components of its imports from North Korea.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/forbes/2010/0809/opinions-north-korea-india-blockade-heads-up.html|title=Look Who's Helping North Korea|last=Bahree|first=Megha|date=August 9, 2010|newspaper=[[Forbes]] |access-date=December 21, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120724045610/http://www.forbes.com/forbes/2010/0809/opinions-north-korea-india-blockade-heads-up.html|archive-date=July 24, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> India participated in the sixth Pyongyang Autumn International Trade Fair in October 2010 and there have been efforts to bring about greater economic cooperation and trade between the two countries since then.<ref name=\"telegraphindia\" /><ref name=\"thehindu\" /> In 2010–11, Indo–North Korean trade stood at $572 million with India's exports accounting for $329 million. India has been providing training to North Korea's citizens in areas like science and technology and IT through agreements for such cooperation between Indian and North Korea's agencies and through India's International Technological and Economic Cooperation (ITEC) programme.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.navhindtimes.in/india-news/how-much-it-will-affect-india-north-korea-ties|title=How much it will affect India-North Korea ties|newspaper=[[The Navhind Times]] |access-date=December 21, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130512231603/http://www.navhindtimes.in/india-news/how-much-it-will-affect-india-north-korea-ties|archive-date=May 12, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mea.gov.in/Portal/ForeignRelation/koreadpr-english.pdf|title=India – DPR Korea Relations|publisher=Ministry of External Affairs|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131103094234/http://www.mea.gov.in/Portal/ForeignRelation/koreadpr-english.pdf|archive-date=November 3, 2013|url-status=live|access-date=December 21, 2012}}</ref>{{pb}}In 2002 and 2004, India contributed 2000 tonnes of food grains to help North Korea tide over severe famine-like conditions. In 2010, India responded to North Korea's request for [[food aid]] and made available to it 1,300 tonnes of [[Pulse (food)|pulse]] and [[wheat]] worth $1 million through the UN [[World Food Programme]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailynk.com/english/read.php?cataId=nk00100&num=7506|title=India Gives Food Aid as U.S.-SK Think|date=March 28, 2011 |publisher=[[Daily NK]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130512000008/http://www.dailynk.com/english/read.php?cataId=nk00100&num=7506|archive-date=May 12, 2013|url-status=live|access-date=December 21, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.firstpost.com/world/indias-secret-ish-romance-with-north-korea-160590.html|title=India's secret-ish romance with North Korea|newspaper=FirstPost.com|access-date=December 21, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130320080926/http://www.firstpost.com/world/indias-secret-ish-romance-with-north-korea-160590.html|archive-date=March 20, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Indonesia}}\n|<!--Date started-->\n|See [[Indonesia–North Korea relations|Indonesian–North Korea relations]]{{pb}}[[Indonesia]] maintains cordial relations with North Korea, despite international sanctions and isolation applied upon North Korea concerning its human rights abuses and nuclear missile program,<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/1890431.stm|title=Megawati embarks on Asian tour|date=March 24, 2002 <!-- , 07:48 GMT -->|publisher=BBC|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131103050850/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/1890431.stm|archive-date=November 3, 2013|url-status=live|access-date=June 6, 2013}}</ref> and Indonesia's stronger engagement and partnership with South Korea. Both nations share a relationship that dates back to the [[Sukarno]] and [[Kim Il Sung]] era in the 60s when Sukarno presented Kim Il Sung an orchid that is named [[Kimilsungia]]. Indonesia has an embassy in Pyongyang, while North Korea has an embassy in Jakarta, with cordial diplomatic relations.<ref name=\"JakartaPost1\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2012/05/14/human-rights-concerns-cloud-north-korea-s-leader-visit-ri.html|title=Human rights concerns cloud North Korea's leader visit to RI|author=Bagus BT Saragih|date=May 14, 2012 <!-- , 8:17 AM\n -->|newspaper=The Jakarta Post|access-date=June 6, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130707054502/http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2012/05/14/human-rights-concerns-cloud-north-korea-s-leader-visit-ri.html|archive-date=July 7, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atimes.com/atimes/Korea/LI15Dg01.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100917112155/http://www.atimes.com/atimes/Korea/LI15Dg01.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=September 17, 2010|title=Sun sets on Indonesia's North Korea ties|author=Jeffrey Robertson|date=September 15, 2010|work=[[Asia Times]]|access-date=June 6, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"JakartaGlobe1\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thejakartaglobe.com/archive/the-odd-couple-north-korea-and-indonesia/|title=The odd couple: North Korea and Indonesia|author=Jamil Maidan Flores|date=July 23, 2012|newspaper=Jakarta Globe|access-date=June 6, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131103130601/http://www.thejakartaglobe.com/archive/the-odd-couple-north-korea-and-indonesia/|archive-date=November 3, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> Both nations are members of the [[Non-Aligned Movement]], <s>with a North Korean restaurant in the country currently.</s> <sup>(Closed as of April 2017)</sup> <ref name=\"2013 World Service Poll\">[http://www.globescan.com/images/images/pressreleases/bbc2013_country_ratings/2013_country_rating_poll_bbc_globescan.pdf 2013 World Service Poll] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151010192245/http://www.globescan.com/images/images/pressreleases/bbc2013_country_ratings/2013_country_rating_poll_bbc_globescan.pdf|date=October 10, 2015}} ''[[BBC]]''</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thejakartaglobe.com/archive/north-koreas-hidden-menu/|title=North Korea's Hidden Menu|author=Tash Roslin|date=May 6, 2010|newspaper=Jakarta Globe|access-date=March 10, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140310154202/http://www.thejakartaglobe.com/archive/north-koreas-hidden-menu/|archive-date=March 10, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.antaranews.com/berita/624259/nasib-restoran-korea-utara-di-kelapa-gading-kini|title=Nasib restoran Korea Utara di Kelapa Gading kini|last=antaranews.com|date=April 15, 2017|website=Antara News|access-date=December 5, 2019|archive-date=April 5, 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230405115403/https://www.antaranews.com/berita/624259/nasib-restoran-korea-utara-di-kelapa-gading-kini|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Iran}}\n|<!--Date started-->\n|See [[Iran–North Korea relations]]{{pb}}Iran–North Korea relations are described as being positive by official news agencies of the two countries. Diplomatic relations picked up following the [[Iranian Revolution]] in 1979 and the establishment of an [[Velayat-e-faqih|Islamic Republic]]. [[Iran]] and North Korea pledged cooperation in educational, scientific, and cultural spheres,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www2.irna.com/en/news/view/line-17/0701233718200902.htm|title=Result of Iranian delegation visit to N Korea positive|date=January 23, 2007|access-date=April 24, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929102650/http://www2.irna.com/en/news/view/line-17/0701233718200902.htm|archive-date=September 29, 2007|url-status=dead|publisher=IRNA}}</ref> as well as cooperating in the [[nuclear program of Iran]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml?xml=/news/2007/01/24/wiran24.xml|title=N. Korea helping Iran with nuclear testing|last=Coughlin|first=Con|date=January 26, 2007|work=The Daily Telegraph|access-date=April 24, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070518114243/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml?xml=/news/2007/01/24/wiran24.xml|archive-date=May 18, 2007|url-status=dead|location=London}}</ref> The United States has expressed its opposition towards North Korea's arms deals with Iran, which started during the 1980s during the [[Iran–Iraq War]], as well as selling domestically produced weapons to Iran, with former US President [[George W. Bush]] labelling North Korea, Iran, and Iraq under [[Saddam Hussein]] as part of the \"[[Axis of evil]]\", in his conception.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Israel}}\n|<!--Date started-->\n|See [[Israel–North Korea relations]]{{pb}}North Korean-Israeli relations are \"perhaps the most estranged 'non-relations'\" in the international community.<ref>{{Cite journal|url = https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/23739770.2016.1177779|doi = 10.1080/23739770.2016.1177779|title = North Korea and Israel: A Missed Opportunity?|year = 2016|last1 = Shai|first1 = Aron|journal = Israel Journal of Foreign Affairs|volume = 10|pages = 59–73|s2cid = 147966445|access-date = July 25, 2021|archive-date = July 25, 2021|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20210725110135/https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/23739770.2016.1177779|url-status = live|url-access = subscription}}</ref> Israeli–North Korea relations are tense, and North Korea does not recognise the state of Israel, denouncing it as an 'imperialist satellite'.<ref name=\"Haggard\">{{cite journal|last=Haggard|first=M|year=1965|title=North Korea's International Position|journal=[[Asian Survey]]|location=[[California]], [[United States]]|volume=5|issue=8|pages=375–88|doi=10.2307/2642410|issn=0004-4687|jstor=2642410|oclc=48536955}}</ref> Since 1988 it recognises the sovereignty of the [[State of Palestine]] over the territory held by Israel.{{pb}}Over the years, North Korea has supplied missile technology to Israel's neighbours, including [[Iran]], [[Syria]], [[Libya]], and [[Egypt]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/Threats_to_Israel/Korea.html|title=North Korea Military Threat to Israel – Jewish Virtual Library|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150219160909/http://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/Threats_to_Israel/Korea.html|archive-date=February 19, 2015|url-status=live|access-date=February 19, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.haaretz.com/news/israel-north-korea-supplying-weapons-to-six-mideast-states-1.254939|title=Israel: North Korea supplying weapons to six Mideast states|date=October 4, 2008|work=Haaretz|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150219172250/http://www.haaretz.com/news/israel-north-korea-supplying-weapons-to-six-mideast-states-1.254939|archive-date=February 19, 2015|url-status=live|access-date=February 19, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailystar.com.lb/article.asp?edition_id=10&categ_id=2&article_id=114766#axzz0rrwU40Mv|title=Israel: North Korea shipping WMDs to Syria|work=The Daily Star Newspaper – Lebanon|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100725112658/http://www.dailystar.com.lb/article.asp?edition_id=10&categ_id=2&article_id=114766|archive-date=July 25, 2010|url-status=live|access-date=February 19, 2015}}</ref> Syria, which has a history of confrontations with Israel, has long maintained a relationship with North Korea based on the cooperation between their respective nuclear programs. On September 6, 2007, the [[Israeli Air Force]] conducted an [[Operation Orchard|airstrike]] on a target in the Deir ez-Zor region of Syria. According to Media and IAEA investigative reports, 10 North Korean nuclear scientists were killed during the airstrike.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=newsarchive&sid=aErPTWRFZpJI&refer=japan|title=North Koreans May Have Died in Israel Attack on Syria, NHK Says|publisher=Bloomberg|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121103011551/http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=newsarchive&sid=aErPTWRFZpJI&refer=japan|archive-date=November 3, 2012|url-status=live|access-date=February 19, 2015}}</ref>{{pb}}When North Korea opened up for Western tourists in 1986 it excluded citizens of Israel along with those of Japan, the United States, and [[South Africa under apartheid|South Africa]].<ref name=\"Koh\">{{cite journal|last=Koh|first=B|year=1988|title=North Korea in 1987: Launching a New Seven-Year Plan|journal=Asian Survey|location=California, United States|volume=28|issue=1|pages=62–70|doi=10.2307/2644873|jstor=2644873|issn=0004-4687|oclc=48536955}}</ref> It has been suggested that North Korea has sought to model its nuclear weapons program on Israel's, as \"a small-state deterrent for a country surrounded by powerful enemies; to display enough activity to make possession of a nuclear device plausible to the outside world, but with no announcement of possession: in short, to appear to arm itself with an ultimate trump card and keep everyone guessing whether and when the weapons might become available.\"<ref name=\"Cha\">{{cite journal|last=Cha|first=Victor|year=2002|title=North Korea's Weapons of Mass Destruction: Badges, Shields, or Swords?|journal=[[Political Science Quarterly]]|location=[[New York City|New York]], United States|volume=117|issue=2|pages=209–30|doi=10.2307/798181|issn=0032-3195|jstor=798181|oclc=39064101}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{flag|Kyrgyzstan}}\n|<!--Date started-->1992\n|Kyrgyzstan and North Korea established formal relations in 1992.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Список стран, с которыми КР установил дипломатические отношения |url=http://mfa.gov.kg/kg/osnovnoe-menyu/vneshnyaya-politika/mezhdunarodnye-dogovory/spisok-stran-s-kotorymi-ustanovleny-dipotnosheniya/spisok-stran-s-kotorymi-kr-ustanovil-diplomaticheskie-otnosheniya |access-date=November 23, 2022 |website=mfa.gov.kg |language=kg |archive-date=October 15, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221015023833/https://mfa.gov.kg/kg/osnovnoe-menyu/vneshnyaya-politika/mezhdunarodnye-dogovory/spisok-stran-s-kotorymi-ustanovleny-dipotnosheniya/spisok-stran-s-kotorymi-kr-ustanovil-diplomaticheskie-otnosheniya |url-status=live }}</ref> Kyrgyzstan is the only country that allows North Koreans to travel to the country without a [[travel visa]] and grants unlimited stay.<ref>{{Cite web |title=North Korea Passport Dashboard {{!}} Passport Index 2022 |url=https://www.passportindex.org/passport/north-korea/ |access-date=November 23, 2022 |website=Passport Index - Global Mobility Intelligence |language=en |archive-date=November 23, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221123045951/https://www.passportindex.org/passport/north-korea/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Visa issues |url=http://mfa.gov.kg/en/Menu---Foreign-/Consular-issues/Visa-issues/akistran |access-date=November 23, 2022 |website=mfa.gov.kg |language=en |archive-date=November 23, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221123045958/https://mfa.gov.kg/en/Menu---Foreign-/Consular-issues/Visa-issues/akistran |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2018, diplomatic talks were held on bilateral relations improving between the two nations.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=President |last2=Parliament |last3=Cabinet |last4=Politics |last5=Economy |last6=Society |last7=Analytics |last8=Regions |last9=Emergencies |title=Kim Jong-un thanks Kyrgyz people and President Jeenbekov for congratulation on DPRK's Foundation Day |url=http://en.kabar.kg/news/kim-jong-un-thanks-kyrgyz-people-and-president-jeenbekov-for-congratulation-on-dprks-foundation-day/ |access-date=November 23, 2022 |website=Информационное Агентство Кабар |language=en |archive-date=November 23, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221123045952/http://en.kabar.kg/news/kim-jong-un-thanks-kyrgyz-people-and-president-jeenbekov-for-congratulation-on-dprks-foundation-day/ |url-status=live }}</ref>\n|- align=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Japan}}\n|<!--Date started-->\n|See [[Japan–North Korea relations]]{{pb}}Japan, along with South Korea, France and the United States, is one of the few countries that has no relations with North Korea. Historical hostility has resulted in incidents of confrontation between the two countries as well.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dw.com/en/north-koreans-in-japan-sense-growing-hostility/a-38609625|title=North Koreans in Japan sense growing hostility|first=Julian|last=Ryall|publisher=Deutsche Welle|date=April 27, 2017|access-date=April 11, 2021|archive-date=May 30, 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230530060516/https://www.dw.com/en/north-koreans-in-japan-sense-growing-hostility/a-38609625|url-status=live}}</ref>{{pb}}However, numerous groups within Japan support North Korea. In May 2017, a delegation of officials from the {{ill|Korean Youth League in Japan|ja|在日本朝鮮青年同盟}} visited the birthplace of Kim Il Sung in [[Mangyongdae]], touring the Mangyongdae Revolutionary Museum, the Korean Revolution Museum, the Mangyongdae Schoolchildren's Palace, and so on as part of their visit.<ref>Rodong News Team, ''[http://www.rodong.rep.kp/en/index.php?strPageID=SF01_02_01&newsID=2017-05-06-0006 Delegation of Korean Youths in Japan Visits Mangyongdae] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170507230507/http://www.rodong.rep.kp/en/index.php?strPageID=SF01_02_01&newsID=2017-05-06-0006|date=May 7, 2017}}'', [[Rodong Sinmun]], May 6, 2017.</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Laos}}\n|<!--Date started-->\n|Laos maintains an embassy in Pyongyang, with Laos being a similar state ideologically.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vietnam-embassy.org/laos-north-korea-pyongyang.html|title=Vietnam-Embassy.org|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160204200337/http://www.vietnam-embassy.org/laos-north-korea-pyongyang.html|archive-date=February 4, 2016|url-status=live|access-date=January 29, 2016}}</ref> In February 2016 [[Kim Yong-chol]] made an official visit to [[Bounnhang Vorachith]].\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Malaysia}}\n|<!--Date started--> 1973{{pb}}'''(suspended 19 March 2021)'''\n|See [[Malaysia–North Korea relations]]{{pb}}Following the assassination of [[Kim Jong-nam]] at [[Kuala Lumpur International Airport]] in February 2017, relations between both countries deteriorated.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thesundaily.my/node/431343|title=N. Korean ambassador given 48 hours to leave Malaysia|author=Ashwin Kumar|date=March 4, 2017|newspaper=[[The Sun (Malaysia)]]|access-date=March 4, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170304174816/http://www.thesundaily.my/node/431343|archive-date=March 4, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/mar/02/kim-jong-nam-malaysia-scraps-visa-free-entry-for-north-koreans|title=Kim Jong-nam death: Malaysia scraps visa-free entry for North Koreans|date=March 2, 2017|agency=[[Associated Press]]|work=[[The Guardian]]|archive-url=https://archive.today/20170307070049/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/mar/02/kim-jong-nam-malaysia-scraps-visa-free-entry-for-north-koreans|archive-date=March 7, 2017|url-status=live|access-date=March 2, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/02/malaysia-north-korea-row-escalates-kim-jong-nam-170220033146607.html|title=Malaysia-North Korea row escalates over Kim Jong-nam|date=February 20, 2017|publisher=Al Jazeera|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170222040532/http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/02/malaysia-north-korea-row-escalates-kim-jong-nam-170220033146607.html|archive-date=February 22, 2017|url-status=live|access-date=February 20, 2017}}</ref> On March 19, 2021, North Korea severed diplomatic relations with Malaysia due to the extradition of North Korean businessman Mul Chol Myong to the United States on money laundering charges. In response, the Malaysia Government defended the integrity of its judicial system and ordered all North Korean diplomats to leave Malaysia.<ref>{{Cite news|title=North Korea says it will sever ties with Malaysia over extradition of 'innocent citizen' to US|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/asia/north-korea-says-will-sever-ties-malaysia-extradition-citizen-us-14441754|access-date=March 19, 2021|work=[[Channel News Asia]]|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210322070339/https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/asia/north-korea-says-will-sever-ties-malaysia-extradition-citizen-us-14441754|archive-date=March 22, 2021|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|date=March 19, 2021|title=MALAYSIA DEEPLY REGRETS THE DPRK'S DECISION TO SEVER TIES 19 MARCH 2021|url=https://www.kln.gov.my/web/guest/-/malaysia-deeply-regrets-the-dprk-s-decision-to-sever-ties-19-march-2021| access-date=March 19, 2021|publisher=[[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Malaysia)|Malaysia Ministry of Foreign Affairs]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210319102706/https://www.kln.gov.my/web/guest/-/malaysia-deeply-regrets-the-dprk-s-decision-to-sever-ties-19-march-2021|archive-date=March 19, 2021|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Ng |first1=Eileen |title= N. Korean diplomats leaving Malaysia after ties are severed |url=https://apnews.com/article/world-news-kuala-lumpur-north-korea-assassinations-malaysia-d6631a39464cf514ce708b5ffde1323f |access-date=March 23, 2021 |work=[[Associated Press]] |date=March 22, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210322013128/https://apnews.com/article/world-news-kuala-lumpur-north-korea-assassinations-malaysia-d6631a39464cf514ce708b5ffde1323f |archive-date=March 22, 2021}}</ref>{{pb}}Previously North Korea had maintained friendly diplomatic ties with Malaysia, with an embassy in Kuala Lumpur while Malaysia had an embassy in Pyongyang.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kln.gov.my/web/guest/foreign-mission-in-malaysia1?p_p_id=foreginmission_WAR_foreginmission5231&p_p_lifecycle=0&p_p_state=normal&p_p_mode=view&p_p_col_id=118_INSTANCE_N6Gk_column-1&p_p_col_count=2&_foreginmission_WAR_foreginmission5231_struts_action=/foreginmission/foreignmission_action&_foreginmission_WAR_foreginmission5231_CMD=detail&_foreginmission_WAR_foreginmission5231_re|title=Embassy of the Democratic People's Republic of Korea|publisher=Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Malaysia|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203164613/http://www.kln.gov.my/web/guest/foreign-mission-in-malaysia1?p_p_id=foreginmission_WAR_foreginmission5231&p_p_lifecycle=0&p_p_state=normal&p_p_mode=view&p_p_col_id=118_INSTANCE_N6Gk_column-1&p_p_col_count=2&_foreginmission_WAR_foreginmission5231_struts_action=/foreginmission/foreignmission_action&_foreginmission_WAR_foreginmission5231_CMD=detail&_foreginmission_WAR_foreginmission5231_recId=573|archive-date=February 3, 2014|url-status=dead|access-date=January 24, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kln.gov.my/web/prk_pyongyang/home|title=Official Website of Embassy of Malaysia, Pyongyang|publisher=[[Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Malaysia]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203164606/http://www.kln.gov.my/web/prk_pyongyang/home|archive-date=February 3, 2014|url-status=dead|access-date=January 24, 2014}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Mongolia}}\n|<!--Date started-->1948\n|See [[Mongolia–North Korea relations]]{{pb}}North Korea–Mongolia relations date back to 1948, when the [[Mongolian People's Republic]] recognized Kim Il Sung's Soviet-backed government in the North. Mongolia also provided assistance to the North during the Korean War. The two countries signed their first friendship and cooperation treaty in 1986.<ref name=\"Kyodo\">{{cite news|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0WDQ/is_2002_August_12/ai_90297096|title=Mongolia, N. Korea sign friendship treaty|date=August 12, 2002|access-date=August 22, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071026011320/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0WDQ/is_2002_August_12/ai_90297096|archive-date=October 26, 2007|url-status=live|publisher=Kyodo}}</ref> Kim Il Sung also paid a visit to the country in 1988.<ref name=\"UBPost\">{{cite news|url=http://ubpost.mongolnews.mn/content/view/446/37/|title=North Korean Kim visits Mongolia|last=Ch.|first=Sumiyabazar|date=July 20, 2007|access-date=August 22, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070812030253/http://ubpost.mongolnews.mn/content/view/446/37/|archive-date=August 12, 2007|url-status=dead|publisher=The UB Post}}</ref> However, relations became strained after the collapse of the Communist government in Mongolia in 1992. The two countries nullified their earlier friendship and cooperation treaty in 1995, and in 1999, North Korea closed its embassy in [[Ulaanbaatar]] during an official visit by [[Kim Dae-jung]], the first-ever such visit by a [[President of South Korea|South Korean president]].<ref name=\"Kyodo\" /> Mongolia had previously expelled two North Korean diplomats but later pursued a policy of engagement.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.atimes.com/koreas/CF16Dg01.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010725055401/http://atimes.com/koreas/CF16Dg01.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=July 25, 2001|title=Pyongyang Watch|last=Foster-Carter|first=Aidan|date=June 16, 2001|access-date=August 22, 2007|work=Asia Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Batchimeg|first=Migeddorj|date=March–April 2006|title=Mongolia's DPRK Policy: Engaging North Korea|journal=Asian Survey|volume=46|issue=2|pages=275–97|doi=10.1525/as.2006.46.2.275}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Myanmar}}\n|<!--Date started-->May 1975\n|See [[Myanmar–North Korea relations]]{{pb}}[[Myanmar]] (formerly Burma) and North Korea established bilateral diplomatic relations in May 1975.{{sfn|Selth|2004|p=4}} The history of contacts between the two countries goes back to 1948, the year of the declaration of Burmese independence. Initially however, Myanmar under [[U Nu]] favored [[Syngman Rhee]]'s government in the south of Korea.{{sfn|Selth|2004|p=1}} During and after the Korean War, Myanmar balanced the interest of North and South Korea, taking into consideration the position of China.{{sfn|Selth|2004|pp=2–3}} After the 1975 establishment of diplomatic relations, Myanmar began to shift toward North Korea, which was also nominally socialist and equally wary of both US and China.{{sfn|Selth|2004|p=5}}{{pb}}The [[Rangoon bombing]] on October 9, 1983, was a turning point in Myanmar–North Korea relations. Once it found out that North Koreans were behind the attack, Myanmar cut off diplomatic relations and went as far as withdrawing formal recognition of the country.{{sfn|Selth|2004|p=10}} Relations began to recover during the years of the Sunshine Policy when South Korea encouraged the North's rapprochement with Myanmar.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://asia.nikkei.com/Politics/Why-Myanmar-North-Korea-are-keeping-their-own-time|title=Why Myanmar, North Korea are keeping their own time|last=Steinberg|first=David I.|date=August 11, 2015|work=[[Nikkei Asia]]|access-date=September 29, 2018|archive-date=September 23, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210923061955/https://asia.nikkei.com/Politics/Why-Myanmar-North-Korea-are-keeping-their-own-time|url-status=dead}}</ref> Strategic considerations brought Myanmar and North Korea even closer. Myanmar had natural resources that North Korea needed, and North Korea began supplying Myanmar with military technology.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.asiantribune.com/?q=node/13797|title=The 4th Burmese Empire with Nuclear Weapon|last=Win|first=Kanbawza|date=October 21, 2008|work=Asian Tribune|access-date=October 1, 2018|archive-date=October 2, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181002215154/http://www.asiantribune.com/?q=node/13797|url-status=dead}}</ref> Diplomatic relations were restored on April 25, 2007.{{sfn|Hoare|2012|p=l}}{{pb}}Military cooperation between North Korea and Myanmar deepened into cooperation with nuclear issues. Myanmar is believed to operate a nuclear weapons program that seeks to emulate the success of North Korea's nuclear weapons capability.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://yaleglobal.yale.edu/content/burmas-nuclear-temptation|title=Burma's Nuclear Temptation|last=Lintner|first=Bertil|date=December 3, 2008|work=YaleGlobal Online|access-date=October 1, 2018|archive-date=October 26, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201026115126/https://yaleglobal.yale.edu/content/burmas-nuclear-temptation|url-status=live}}</ref> The program is supported by North Korean training and equipment. Although the [[2011–2015 Myanmar political reforms]] have led to the cancellation or downgrading of military ties,{{sfn|Seekins|2017|p=308}} reports on suspicious activities have continued {{as of|2018|lc=yes}}.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/02/north-korea-arming-syria-myanmar-report-180203064444145.html|title=North Korea arming Syria, Myanmar: UN report|date=February 3, 2018|publisher=Al Jazeera|access-date=September 29, 2018|agency=AFP|archive-date=July 24, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190724072422/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/02/north-korea-arming-syria-myanmar-report-180203064444145.html|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Pakistan}}\n|<!--Date started-->\n|See [[North Korea–Pakistan relations]]{{pb}}Pakistan maintains warm diplomatic and trade relations with North Korea, while still maintaining friendly relations with South Korea. The start of relations between the two countries emerged sometime in the 1970s during the rule of Pakistani [[Prime Minister]] [[Zulfikar Ali Bhutto]]. North Korea maintains an embassy in [[Islamabad]]. Relations between the two countries are reported to have been strong in the past and North Korea has supplied missile technology to Pakistan even as the populace of Pakistan is divided on North Korea.<ref name=\"2013 World Service Poll\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pakistan-facts.com/staticpages/index.php?page=20030111164804284|title=Pakistan-North Korea Connection Creates Huge Dilemma For U.S.|last=Carbaugh|first=John E.|work=Pakistan-Facts.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070701103529/http://www.pakistan-facts.com/staticpages/index.php?page=20030111164804284|archive-date=July 1, 2007|url-status=usurped|access-date=May 31, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/3467219.stm|title=BBC NEWS – South Asia – Powell says nuclear ring broken|date=February 6, 2004 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130423221946/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/3467219.stm|archive-date=April 23, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/6033457.stm|title=BBC NEWS – Asia-Pacific – Outcry at N Korea 'nuclear test'|date=October 9, 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070316002607/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/6033457.stm|archive-date=March 16, 2007|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Palestine}}\n|<!--Date started-->1966\n|See [[North Korea–Palestine relations]]{{pb}}North Korea established relations with the [[Palestine Liberation Organization]] in 1966.{{sfn|Wertz|Oh|Kim|2016|p=3}} Beyond this, North Korea has long seen Israel as an \"imperialist satellite\" and recognizes the sovereignty of Palestine over all territory held by Israel, excluding the [[Golan Heights]], which is considered as Syrian Territory.<ref name=\"Haggard\" /> After the demise of the [[Soviet Union]], North Korea's involvement in the [[Israeli–Palestinian conflict]] declined and North Korea shifted from the exporting of revolution to pragmatism.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.country-data.com/cgi-bin/query/r-9642.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090917120827/http://www.country-data.com/cgi-bin/query/r-9642.html|url-status=dead|title=North Korea - Relations with the Third World|archive-date=September 17, 2009|website=country-data.com}}</ref> During the [[Gaza War (2008–09)]] North Korea harshly condemned Israeli actions, with a Foreign Ministry spokesman denounced the killing of unarmed civilians and called it a crime against humanity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2008-12/30/content_10581934.htm|title=DPRK denounces Israel for bombarding Gaza|date=December 30, 2008|publisher=News.xinhuanet.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121023123922/http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2008-12/30/content_10581934.htm|archive-date=October 23, 2012|url-status=dead|access-date=September 19, 2009}}</ref> Later, on the floor of the [[UN General Assembly]] North Korea permanent representative [[Sin Son-ho]] said that North Korea \"fully supported Palestinians' struggle to expel Israeli aggressors from their Territory and restore their right to self-determination.\"<ref>UNGA10807</ref> After the [[2010 Gaza flotilla raid]] North Korea Foreign Ministry called the attack a \"crime against humanity\" perpetrated under the guidance of the United States, with North Korea also expressing full support for the self-determination of the Palestinian Arabs.<ref>[http://www.kcna.co.jp/index-e.htm News From Korean Central News Agency Of Dprk] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090910114906/http://www.kcna.co.jp/index-e.htm|date=September 10, 2009}}. Kcna.co.jp. Retrieved on June 19, 2010.</ref> During the [[2014 Israel-Gaza conflict]], the Foreign Ministry issued a statement that read: \"We bitterly denounce Israel's brutal killings of many defenseless Palestinians through indiscriminate military attacks on peaceable residential areas in Palestine as they are unpardonable crimes against humanity.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kcna.kp/kcna.user.article.retrieveNewsViewInfoList.kcmsf#this|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170304112449/http://www.kcna.kp/kcna.user.article.retrieveNewsViewInfoList.kcmsf|url-status=dead|title=조선중앙통신|archive-date=March 4, 2017}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Philippines}}\n|<!--Date started-->2000\n|See [[North Korea–Philippines relations]]{{pb}}In 2000, the Philippines and North Korea established diplomatic relations after more than 20 years of negotiations. Trade between the two countries remains almost non-existent as a trade embargo remains in place. In 2007, the agreement was boosted further and was signed by Philippine Foreign Secretary [[Alberto Romulo]] and North Korean Foreign Minister Pak Ui Chun during the Association of South-east Asian Nations (ASEAN) meeting in Manila.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.monstersandcritics.com/news/asiapacific/news/article_1336146.php/Philippines_North_Korea_agree_to_boost_bilateral_relations_Roundup|title=Philippines, North Korea agree to boost bilateral relations|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101126122107/http://www.monstersandcritics.com/news/asiapacific/news/article_1336146.php/Philippines_North_Korea_agree_to_boost_bilateral_relations_Roundup|archive-date=November 26, 2010|url-status=dead|access-date=July 12, 2011}} Philippines, North Korea agree to boost bilateral relations</ref>{{pb}}The Philippines has a representative in Pyongyang through an embassy in Beijing. North Korea has a representative through its embassy in Bangkok.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Singapore}}\n|<!--Date started-->1975\n|See [[North Korea–Singapore relations]]{{pb}}North Korea maintains an embassy in Singapore.<ref>{{Cite web|last=|date=May 11, 2018|title=North Korea's diplomatic footprint dwarfed by US in Singapore|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/north-koreas-diplomatic-footprint-dwarfed-by-us-in-singapore|access-date=August 12, 2021|website=The Straits Times|language=en|archive-date=April 5, 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230405213816/https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/north-koreas-diplomatic-footprint-dwarfed-by-us-in-singapore|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Sri Lanka}}\n|<!--Date started-->\n|In 1970, North Korea trade delegation's office in [[Colombo]] became an embassy. While in the country, North Korea diplomats cultivated links with the Marxist–Leninist [[Janatha Vimukthi Peramuna]]. In 1971, in the wake of a [[1971 JVP insurrection|failed uprising by the JVP]], the embassy was closed.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nknews.org/2014/03/north-koreas-role-in-sri-lankas-bloody-insurgencies/|title=North Korea's role in Sri Lanka's bloody insurgencies|last=Farrell|first=Tom|date=March 12, 2014|work=[[NK News]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170220171515/https://www.nknews.org/2014/03/north-koreas-role-in-sri-lankas-bloody-insurgencies/|archive-date=February 20, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Syria}}\n|<!--Date started-->\n|See [[North Korea–Syria relations]]{{pb}}[[Syria]] and North Korea have had close relations since the late 1960s, when North Korea provided military assistance to Syria in its wars with Israel.<ref name=\"Taylor\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2016/03/25/are-north-koreans-fighting-in-syria-its-not-as-far-fetched-as-it-sounds/|title=Are North Koreans fighting in Syria? It's not as far-fetched as it sounds.|last=Taylor|first=Adam|date=March 25, 2016|newspaper=Washington Post|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160803141404/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2016/03/25/are-north-koreans-fighting-in-syria-its-not-as-far-fetched-as-it-sounds/|archive-date=August 3, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> They maintain embassies in the other country's respective capitals.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nknews.org/2017/01/a-long-way-from-damascus-life-as-syrias-ambassador-to-north-korea/|title=A long way from Damascus: Life as Syria's ambassador to North Korea|last=O'Carroll|first=Chad|date=January 31, 2017|work=[[NK News]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170203161957/https://www.nknews.org/2017/01/a-long-way-from-damascus-life-as-syrias-ambassador-to-north-korea/|archive-date=February 3, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>{{pb}}North Korea built a nuclear reactor in Syria based on the design of its own reactor at [[Yongbyon]], and North Korean officials traveled regularly to the site. The Syrian reactor [[Operation Orchard|was destroyed]] by Israel in an airstrike in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/12/20/world/asia/in-detecting-kim-jong-il-death-a-gobal-intelligence-failure.html?_r=1&pagewanted=print|title=In Kim Jong-il Death, an Extensive Intelligence Failure|author=Mark Landler, Choe Sang-hun|website=[[The New York Times]]|date=December 19, 2011|access-date=February 19, 2015|archive-date=September 24, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180924055103/https://www.nytimes.com/2011/12/20/world/asia/in-detecting-kim-jong-il-death-a-gobal-intelligence-failure.html?_r=1&pagewanted=print|url-status=live}}</ref> The United States signed the [[Iran North Korea Syria Nonproliferation Act]] in 2000. In 2016, there were reports that North Korean troops were fighting to defend the Syrian government in the [[Syrian Civil War]].<ref name=\"Taylor\" />\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Taiwan}}\n|<!--Date started-->\n|See [[North Korea-Taiwan relations]]{{pb}}The Republic of China ([[Taiwan]]) does not recognise North Korea as a state.{{Citation needed|date=April 2021}}{{pb}}Premier [[Lai Ching-te]] approved a total ban on trade between Taiwan and North Korea in September 2017.<ref name=\"FT\">{{cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/315503b0-0559-11e8-9650-9c0ad2d7c5b5|title=Taiwanese suspected of shipping coal from North Korea to Vietnam|last=White|first=Edward|date=January 29, 2018|newspaper=[[Financial Times]]|archive-url=https://archive.today/20180130015923/https://www.ft.com/content/315503b0-0559-11e8-9650-9c0ad2d7c5b5|archive-date=January 30, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> Taiwanese businessmen have been accused of selling [[coal]], [[oil]] and gas to North Korea, as well as importing North Korean textiles and employing North Koreans in Taiwanese fishing vessels.<ref name=\"FT\" />\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Turkey}}||<!--Date started-->January 15, 2001<ref name=\"auto62\">{{Cite web| url=http://www.mfa.gov.tr/relations-between-turkey-and-the-democratic-peoples-republic-of-korea.en.mfa| title=Relations between Turkey and the Democratic People's Republic of Korea| publisher=Ministry of Foreign Affairs| access-date=October 6, 2020| archive-date=September 12, 2015| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150912225245/http://www.mfa.gov.tr/relations-between-turkey-and-the-democratic-peoples-republic-of-korea.en.mfa| url-status=live}}</ref>|| See [[North Korea–Turkey relations]]\n* The Embassy of [[North Korea]] in [[Sofia]] is accredited to Turkey.<ref name=\"auto62\"/>\n* The Turkish Embassy in [[Seoul]] is accredited to [[North Korea]].<ref name=\"auto62\"/>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Vietnam}}\n|<!--Date started-->\n|See [[North Korea–Vietnam relations]]{{pb}}Students from [[North Vietnam]] began going to North Korea to study as early as the 1960s, even before the formal establishment of Korean-language education in their country.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Le|first=Quang Thiem|date=February 2005|title=Korean Studies in Vietnam|url=http://newsletter.kf.or.kr/english/contents.asp?vol=51&lang=English&no=545|url-status=live|journal=Korea Foundation Newsletter|volume=14|issue=1|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927230335/http://newsletter.kf.or.kr/english/contents.asp?vol=51&lang=English&no=545|archive-date=September 27, 2007|access-date=July 9, 2007}}</ref>{{pb}}North Korea lent material and manpower support to North Vietnam during the [[Vietnam War]], though the number of South Korean troops fighting for South Vietnam was larger.<ref name=\"Hankyoreh\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.hani.co.kr/h21/vietnam/Eng-vietnam273.html|title=The secret tragedy of Vietnam|last=Ku|first=Su-Jeong|date=September 2, 1999|periodical=The Hankyoreh|access-date=March 27, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070526063209/http://www.hani.co.kr/h21/vietnam/Eng-vietnam273.html|archive-date=May 26, 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"atimes\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.atimes.com/atimes/Korea/HH18Dg02.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060923224111/http://www.atimes.com/atimes/Korea/HH18Dg02.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=September 23, 2006|title=Missiles and madness|last=Bennett|first=Richard M.|date=August 18, 2006|periodical=Asia Times|access-date=March 27, 2007}}</ref> As a result of a decision of the [[Korean Workers' Party]] in October 1966, in early 1967 North Korea sent a fighter squadron to North Vietnam to back up the North Vietnamese 921st and 923rd fighter squadrons defending Hanoi. They stayed through 1968; 200 pilots were reported to have served.<ref name=\"atimes\" /> In addition, at least two anti-aircraft artillery regiments were sent as well. North Korea also sent weapons, ammunition and two million sets of uniforms to their comrades in North Vietnam.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Pribbenow|first=Merle|year=2003|title=The 'Ology War: technology and ideology in the Vietnamese defense of Hanoi, 1967|journal=Journal of Military History|volume=67|issue=1|page=183|doi=10.1353/jmh.2003.0066|doi-access=}}</ref> Kim Il Sung is reported to have told his pilots to \"fight in the war as if the Vietnamese sky were their own\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/1427367.stm|title=N Korea admits Vietnam war role|last=Gluck|first=Caroline|date=July 27, 2001|periodical=BBC News|access-date=March 27, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080308081855/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/1427367.stm|archive-date=March 8, 2008|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/696970.stm|title=North Korea fought in Vietnam War|date=March 31, 2000|periodical=BBC News|access-date=March 27, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080308081900/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/696970.stm|archive-date=March 8, 2008|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/1435540.stm|title=North Korea honours Vietnam war dead|date=July 12, 2001|periodical=BBC News|access-date=October 19, 2006|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080308081852/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/1435540.stm|archive-date=March 8, 2008|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|}\n\n\n===Europe===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:100%; margin:auto;\"\n! style=\"width:15%;\" |Country\n! style=\"width:12%;\" |Formal Relations Began\n!Notes\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|European Union}}\n|<!--Date started-->\n|{{see also|North Korea–European Union relations}}North Korea had economic interests in the European Union. In March 2002, North Korea's trade minister visited certain EU member states, including [[Belgium]], [[Italy]], the [[United Kingdom]], and [[Sweden]], and the country has also been known to send short-term trainees to Europe. Additionally, workshops regarding North Korea's economic reform have taken place with EU diplomats and economists as participants.<ref>{{cite book|title=21st century NEA relations and human rights in North Korea|last=Park|first=Youngho|year=2006|isbn=978-8988435830|page=245|publisher=백산 자료원 }}</ref> The EU still is concerned about human rights violations occurring within the country and has hosted talks with North Korean defectors.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Albania}}\n|<!--Date started--> November 28, 1948\n|{{See also|Albania–North Korea relations}}Diplomatic relations with Albania were established on November 28, 1948.{{Citation needed|date=May 2024}} [[People's Socialist Republic of Albania|Albania]]'s communist government led by [[Enver Hoxha]] was often likened to the isolation of North Korea.<ref name=\"balkaninsight\" /> In 1961, Albania and North Korea signed a joint declaration of friendship.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://digitalarchive.wilsoncenter.org/document/114408|title=Wilson Center Digital Archive|website=digitalarchive.wilsoncenter.org|access-date=January 2, 2020|archive-date=January 2, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200102205918/https://digitalarchive.wilsoncenter.org/document/114408|url-status=live}}</ref> In the 1970s, relations between the two countries deteriorated, with Hoxha writing in June 1977 that [[Kim Il Sung]] and the leadership of the [[Korean Workers' Party]] had betrayed the Korean people by accepting aid from other countries, primarily between countries in the [[Eastern Bloc]] and [[Non-Aligned Movement|non-aligned]] countries such as [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|Yugoslavia]]. As a result, relations between North Korea and Albania would remain low until Hoxha's death in 1985. In 2012, the [[president of the Presidium of the Supreme People's Assembly|President of the Supreme People's Assembly]] [[Kim Yong-nam]] sent a congratulatory message to Albanian President [[Bujar Nishani]] on the [[100th Anniversary of the Independence of Albania]].<ref name=\"balkaninsight\">{{Cite web|url=https://balkaninsight.com/2012/11/30/north-korea-s-leader-wishes-albania-prosperity/|title=Reclusive North Korea Salutes Albanian Birthday|date=November 30, 2012|access-date=January 2, 2020|archive-date=January 2, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200102205923/https://balkaninsight.com/2012/11/30/north-korea-s-leader-wishes-albania-prosperity/|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Austria}}\n|<!--Date started-->\n|Diplomatic relations between [[Austria]] and North Korea have consistently been rather close, with the former President of Austria [[Heinz Fischer]] having been a founding member and co-chairman in the ''Austria-DPRK Friendship Organization(조선.오스트리아친선협회(오지리))''. With the changes in government in 2000 and 2017 respectively, relations took a light hit, with the parties in coalition, namely the [[ÖVP]] and [[FPÖ]], generally utilizing an anti-North Korean stance and using such to defame their political opponents.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unzensuriert.at/content/00691-wann-distanziert-sich-heinz-fischer-endlich-von-nordkorea|title=Wann distanziert sich Heinz Fischer endlich von Nordkorea?|work=Unzensuriert |date=March 20, 2010|access-date=January 2, 2020|archive-date=January 2, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200102205919/https://www.unzensuriert.at/content/00691-wann-distanziert-sich-heinz-fischer-endlich-von-nordkorea|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ots.at/presseaussendung/OTS_20100420_OTS0242/nordkorea-gesellschaft-roter-praesidentschaftskandidat-heinz-fischer-der-unwahrheit-ueberfuehrt|title=Nordkorea-Gesellschaft: Roter Präsidentschaftskandidat Heinz Fischer der Unwahrheit überführt|website=OTS.at|access-date=March 13, 2019|archive-date=April 22, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190422074803/https://www.ots.at/presseaussendung/OTS_20100420_OTS0242/nordkorea-gesellschaft-roter-praesidentschaftskandidat-heinz-fischer-der-unwahrheit-ueberfuehrt|url-status=live}}</ref> Austria was the host of the [[Golden Star Bank]], the last bank instituted and owned by North Korea in Europe.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Bulgaria}}\n|<!--Date started-->November 29, 1948\n|[[Bulgaria]] and North Korea generally have good relations. Diplomatic relations between the countries were established on November 29, 1948, and a bilateral agreement on cultural and scientific cooperation was signed in 1970. [[Kim Il Sung]] visited the [[People's Republic of Bulgaria]] for the first time in the 1950s, and again in 1975. Bulgarian volunteers provided basic aid to North Korea during the [[Korean War]] by providing items such as clothing and foodstuffs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.duma.bg/2005/0905/010905/obshtestvo/ob-5.html|title=Страницата не може да бъде намерена – вестник Дума|archive-url=https://archive.today/20121203022904/http://www.duma.bg/2005/0905/010905/obshtestvo/ob-5.html|archive-date=December 3, 2012|url-status=dead|access-date=August 12, 2008}}</ref> Even after the fall of [[communism]] in [[Eastern Europe]], the countries retained active diplomatic relations. The foreign language institute in Pyongyang maintains a [[Bulgarian language]] department. In the past, the two countries also cooperated closely in the sphere of sports, and still maintain such cooperation albeit to a lesser degree. In 2017, the primer of North Korea, Pak Pong Ju, sent a message to [[Boyko Borisov]], congratulating him on his appointment as prime minister of Bulgaria, saying that \"relations of friendship and cooperation between the two countries\" should favorably develop \"in common interests\". The same day, North Korea's foreign minister, Ri Yong Ho, sent a message, similar in content, to [[Ekaterina Gecheva-Zaharieva]], congratulating her on \"appointment as vice prime minister and foreign minister of Bulgaria\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kcna.co.jp/item/2017/201705/news07/20170507-11ee.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191124001850/http://www.kcna.co.jp/item/2017/201705/news07/20170507-11ee.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=November 24, 2019|title=Greetings to Bulgarian PM|date=May 7, 2017|agency=KCNA}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Belarus}}\n|<!--Date started-->1992\n|Diplomatic relations were established in 1992.<ref name=\":25\">{{Cite news|url=http://neweasterneurope.eu/2016/09/27/north-korean-embassy-in-belarus-diplomatic-symbolism-economic-horizons/|title=The North Korean Embassy in Belarus. Diplomatic symbolism, economic horizons|date=September 27, 2016|work=New Eastern Europe|access-date=July 12, 2019|language=en-GB|archive-date=July 12, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190712133843/http://neweasterneurope.eu/2016/09/27/north-korean-embassy-in-belarus-diplomatic-symbolism-economic-horizons/|url-status=live}}</ref> Since 2016, North Korea has operated an embassy in [[Minsk]], opened in 2016,<ref name=\":25\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://belarusfeed.com/now-officially-north-korea-open-embassy-in-minsk/|title=Now OFFICIALLY: North Korea Opens Embassy In Minsk|date=September 27, 2016|work=BelarusFeed|access-date=September 15, 2018|language=en-US|archive-date=September 15, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180915192407/http://belarusfeed.com/now-officially-north-korea-open-embassy-in-minsk/|url-status=dead}}</ref> while Belarus has a consulate in [[South Hamgyong Province|Hamgyong-namdo]], despite the fact that the Belarusian government recognizes this as a trade mission and works through other representatives in [[Moscow]] (Russia).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://world.kbs.co.kr/english/news/news_In_detail.htm?No=122157|title=Belarus Denies N. Korea's Claim of Embassy Opening|date=September 29, 2016|website=KBS World Radio|language=En|access-date=September 15, 2018|archive-date=September 15, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180915192536/http://world.kbs.co.kr/english/news/news_In_detail.htm?No=122157|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mfa.gov.by/upload/Dip-En-01-17.pdf|title=Embassies, Consulates and Representations of International Organisations in Belarus|date=January 2017|website=Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the Republic of Belarus|page=20|access-date=September 15, 2018|archive-date=September 15, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180915192535/http://mfa.gov.by/upload/Dip-En-01-17.pdf|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mfa.gov.by/upload/Dip-En-01-17.pdf|title=Embassies, Consulates and Representations of International Organisations in Belarus|date=January 2017|website=Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the Republic of Belarus|pages=26–27|access-date=September 15, 2018|archive-date=September 15, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180915192535/http://mfa.gov.by/upload/Dip-En-01-17.pdf|url-status=live}}</ref> North Korean [[Eternal leaders of North Korea#Presidency of North Korea before 1994|President]] [[Kim Il Sung]] visited [[Minsk]], the capital of the [[Belarusian SSR]] in 1984. During the visit, he visited the Minsk Tractor Works and the [[Brest Fortress]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.tut.by/society/509875.html|title=С эскортом по Ленинскому проспекту. Как Минск встречал Фиделя Кастро, Ким Ир Сена и Жоржа Помпиду|date=August 28, 2016|website=TUT.BY|access-date=July 12, 2019|archive-date=July 12, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190712133245/https://news.tut.by/society/509875.html|url-status=dead}}</ref>{{pb}}In 2020, Belarusian President [[Aleksandr Lukashenko]] suggested improving the relations between North Korea and Belarus, stating that the relations are on an \"unreasonably low level\". He stated that the relations should be improved with a focus on \"medication and food production, professional training and professional development\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nknews.org/2020/11/belarusian-president-wants-to-speed-up-projects-with-north-korea/|title=Belarusian president wants to speed up projects with North Korea|date=November 6, 2020|website=[[NK News]]|access-date=May 24, 2021|archive-date=May 24, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210524194757/https://www.nknews.org/2020/11/belarusian-president-wants-to-speed-up-projects-with-north-korea/|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Denmark}}\n|<!--Date started-->\n|See [[Denmark–North Korea relations]]{{pb}}Denmark is represented in North Korea through its embassy in [[Hanoi]], [[Vietnam]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.um.dk/da/menu/OmOs/Organisation/AmbassaderMv/Asien/DenDemokratiskeFolkerepublikKorea.htm|title=KOREA, DEN DEMOKRATISKE FOLKEREPUBLIK |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101227142508/http://www.um.dk/da/menu/OmOs/Organisation/AmbassaderMv/Asien/DenDemokratiskeFolkerepublikKorea.htm |archive-date=December 27, 2010 |url-status=dead |publisher=Ministry Of Foreign Affairs of Denmark |access-date=July 23, 2010}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Finland}}\n|{{dts|1973|06|01|format=dmy}}\n|See [[Finland–North Korea relations]]{{pb}}[[Finland]] recognised North Korea on April 13, 1973. Diplomatic relations were established on June 1, 1973.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://formin.finland.fi/public/default.aspx?contentid=51864&contentlan=2&culture=en-US|title=North Korea – Ministry for Foreign Affairs of Finland: Entering Finland and travelling abroad: North Korea|website=formin.finland.fi|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170907075437/http://formin.finland.fi/public/default.aspx?contentid=51864&contentlan=2&culture=en-US|archive-date=September 7, 2017|url-status=dead|access-date=September 7, 2017}}</ref> Finland has a resident ambassador posted in [[Seoul]]. North Korea owes the government and other private businesses over 30 million [[Euro]]s that date back to the 1970s. In April 2017 government officials reassured [[Yle|YLE]] news reporters that they have not forgotten about the debt, and will work to find a solution to their debts.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://yle.fi/uutiset/osasto/news/north_korea_owes_finland_millions_in_decades-old_debt/9588973|title=North Korea owes Finland millions in decades-old debt|work=Yle Uutiset|access-date=September 7, 2017|language=en|archive-date=September 7, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170907075741/https://yle.fi/uutiset/osasto/news/north_korea_owes_finland_millions_in_decades-old_debt/9588973|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|France}}\n|<!--Date started-->\n|See [[France–North Korea relations]]{{pb}}Relations between the [[French Republic]] and North Korea are officially non-existent. France is one of only two European Union members not to maintain diplomatic relations with North Korea, the other being Estonia.{{sfn|Wertz|Oh|Kim|2016|pp=1–2}}{{sfn|Wertz|Oh|Kim|2016|pp=8–9}} There is no French [[embassy]], nor any other type of French diplomatic representation, in Pyongyang, and no North Korean embassy in Paris, although a North Korean diplomatic office is located in nearby [[Neuilly-sur-Seine]].<ref name=\"questions.assemblee-nationale.fr\">{{cite web|url=http://questions.assemblee-nationale.fr/q12/12-58175QE.htm|title=FICHE QUESTION|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303200748/http://questions.assemblee-nationale.fr/q12/12-58175QE.htm|archive-date=March 3, 2016|url-status=live|access-date=January 29, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abm.fr/fiche/cdn2a.html|title=Le site de vos voyages|work=ABM Aventure du Bout du Monde|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100104031219/http://www.abm.fr/fiche/cdn2a.html|archive-date=January 4, 2010|url-status=dead|access-date=February 19, 2015}}</ref> France's official position is that it will consider establishing diplomatic relations with North Korea if and when the latter abandons its nuclear weapons program and improves [[Human rights in North Korea|its human rights record]].<ref name=\"questions.assemblee-nationale.fr\" />\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Germany}}\n|1949 (East Germany){{pb}}March 1, 2001 (United Germany)\n|See [[Germany–North Korea relations]]{{pb}}The relations between [[Germany]] and North Korea date back to 1949, when the governments of [[East Germany]] and North Korea established diplomatic relations. The embassies in Berlin and Pyongyang opened 1954. East Germany used to be one of North Korea's closest allies within the Eastern Communist states, so multiple cooperation agreements and trade ties were established. The [[Federal Republic of Germany]] (West Germany) remained in a rather hostile position towards North Korea during the Cold War and only maintained basic diplomatic contact; however in 1981 a delegation of North Korean officials visited Bonn.{{pb}}After the German reunion, [[Germany]] maintained a diplomatic mission in the former [[East Germany|East German]] Embassy and officially opened its embassy in Pyongyang in 2001, while North Korea re-opened its embassy in Berlin the same year.{{pb}}These diplomatic ties are still active, but due to the massive UN sanctions there is very little economic cooperation between the two countries. Also, [[Germany]] has continued to condemn the North Korean nuclear program.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Hungary}}\n|<!--Date started-->\n|See [[Hungary–North Korea relations]]{{pb}}Relations between the two countries have existed since the Korean War; however, conflicts beginning in the late 1980s strained relations.{{pb}}When the [[Hungarian Revolution of 1956]] began, roughly 200 of North Korean students joined in; their war experience proved to be of aid to the Hungarian students.<ref>{{citation|title=<헝가리 혁명 50주년> ④ 북한 유학생도 참가했다/50th Anniversary of the Hungarian Revolution, #4: North Korean Exchange Students Also Participated|date=October 22, 2006|url=http://news.onmam.com/news_content.asp?NewsNum=81829&p_cate_code=002006&linkid=fnews|periodical=[[Yonhap News]]|access-date=April 21, 2009}}{{dead link|date=April 2017|bot=InternetArchiveBot|fix-attempted=yes}}</ref> In the aftermath of the revolution, Hungarian police and Soviet forces gathered up the students from North Korea and deported them back to North Korea, with four of them escaping to Austria.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nkeconwatch.com/2008/08/01/the-usas-first-naturalized-north-korean/|title=The USA's first naturalized North Korean|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170211160136/http://www.nkeconwatch.com/2008/08/01/the-usas-first-naturalized-north-korean/|archive-date=February 11, 2017|url-status=live|access-date=February 11, 2017}}</ref>{{pb}}In 1989, Hungary would become the first [[Eastern Bloc]] nation to [[Hungary–South Korea relations|open relations with South Korea]]; in response, North Korea withdrew [[Kim Pyong-il]] from Hungary and sent him to Bulgaria instead.<ref>{{citation|last=Sano|first=Yoel|title=Happy Birthday, Dear Leader – who's next in line?|date=February 14, 2004|url=http://www.atimes.com/atimes/Korea/FB14Dg04.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040213164807/http://www.atimes.com/atimes/Korea/FB14Dg04.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=February 13, 2004|periodical=Asia Times|access-date=October 25, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Sterngold|first=James|title=Evolution in Europe; Stunned North Korea Warns Soviets on Meeting With Seoul Leader|date=June 2, 1990|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C0CEEDC1E3BF931A35755C0A966958260&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=print|periodical=The New York Times|access-date=October 22, 2007|archive-date=June 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200627125002/https://www.nytimes.com/1990/06/02/world/evolution-europe-stunned-north-korea-warns-soviets-meeting-with-seoul-leader.html|url-status=live}}</ref> In response, North Korea referred to the Hungarian decision as a \"betrayal\", and expelled the Hungarian envoy to Pyongyang.<ref name=\"KT\">{{citation|last=Kim|first=Se-jeong|title=Hungary Fetes 20-Year Ties With Korea|date=February 1, 2009|url=https://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/special/2009/04/176_38755.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120829180139/http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/special/2009/04/176_38755.html|url-status=live|periodical=[[The Korea Times]] |access-date=April 21, 2009|archive-date=August 29, 2012}}</ref> As a result, there was a downturn in bilateral ties which lasted over a decade-and-a-half but in 2004, then-deputy State Secretary [[Gábor Szentiványi]] indicated that his government were interested in improving their relations with North Korea, even though by 2009, the former Hungarian embassy building in Pyongyang remained empty.<ref>{{citation|last=Seo|first=Hyun-jin|title=Hungary ready to improve ties with N. Korea|date=February 2, 2004|url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-20182777_ITM|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121017011602/http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-20182777_ITM|url-status=live|periodical=The Korea Herald; Asia Africa Intelligence Wire|access-date=April 21, 2009|archive-date=October 17, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"KT\" />\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Iceland}}\n|<!--Date started-->\n|See [[Iceland–North Korea relations]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Italy}}\n|January 2000\n|See [[Italy–North Korea relations]]{{pb}}While North Korea was considered isolationist and \"politically reclusive\" by the Italian government for years, in January 2000, Italy announced its opening of official diplomatic relations with North Korea.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/sandiego/access/51420823.html?dids=51420823:51420823&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Mar+17%2C+2000&author=Howard+W.+French&pub=The+San+Diego+Union+-+Tribune&desc=North+Korea+suddenly+makes+diplomatic+waves+%7c+Establishes+ties+with+Italy%2C+sends+out+feelers+to+other+countries|title=North Korea suddenly makes diplomatic waves|last=French|first=Howard W.|date=March 17, 2000|newspaper=San Diego Union-Tribune|access-date=March 21, 2012}}{{dead link|date=July 2024|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=NewsLibrary&p_multi=APAB&d_place=APAB&p_theme=newslibrary2&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0F89AD75C21CFBDB&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D|title=North Korea wages diplomatic campaign with a wary world|date=January 19, 2000|publisher=Associated Press Archive|access-date=March 21, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304132535/http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=NewsLibrary&p_multi=APAB&d_place=APAB&p_theme=newslibrary2&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0F89AD75C21CFBDB&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D|archive-date=March 4, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/01/05/world/italy-opens-north-korea-ties-first-by-a-big-western-nation.html?scp=2&sq=North+Korea&st=nyt|title=Italy Opens North Korea Ties, First by a Big Western Nation|last=Stanley|first=Alessandra|date=January 5, 2000|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=May 7, 2017|archive-date=September 17, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170917080747/http://www.nytimes.com/2000/01/05/world/italy-opens-north-korea-ties-first-by-a-big-western-nation.html?scp=2&sq=North+Korea&st=nyt|url-status=live}}</ref> Later, North Korea's representative for the UN's Food and Agriculture Organization met with Lamberto Dini to formally establish diplomatic ties, with formal ties considered a huge step for North Korea.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atimes.com/koreas/BA07Dg01.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20000925074103/http://atimes.com/koreas/BA07Dg01.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=September 25, 2000|title=Italy brings North Korea out of isolation|work=Asia Times|access-date=March 21, 2012}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Malta}}\n|<!--Date started-->\n|During the Cold War, Malta had good relations with North Korea. The future leader [[Kim Jong Il]] spent a year there learning English in 1973. The Maltese Prime Minister [[Dom Mintoff]] traveled to Pyongyang to meet President [[Kim Il Sung]] in 1982. They signed a secret military agreement whereby North Korea supplied Malta with weapons and military training. In 1984, Malta severed ties with South Korea.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nknews.org/2014/06/kim-jong-ils-unlikely-maltese-mentor-a-secret-military-agreement/|title=Kim Jong Il's unlikely Maltese mentor & a secret military agreement|last=Young|first=Benjamin R|date=June 11, 2014|work=[[NK News]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150417033152/https://www.nknews.org/2014/06/kim-jong-ils-unlikely-maltese-mentor-a-secret-military-agreement/|archive-date=April 17, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Netherlands}}\n|<!--Date started-->2001\n|The [[Netherlands]] and North Korea have maintained diplomatic relations since 2001. In 2011, the two countries celebrated 10 years of diplomatic relations, and for the occasion North Korea showed three Dutch documentaries in Pyongyang, including one about [[Flood control in the Netherlands|Dutch water management]]. Contact with North Korea are maintained by the Dutch ambassador in [[Seoul]], [[South Korea]]. North Korea's embassy in [[Bern]], [[Switzerland]] serves North Korea's interests in the Netherlands. The Netherlands is worried about the violations of human rights and the development of nuclear technologies in North Korea, and has urged North Korea to improve their bilateral relations with South Korea.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rijksoverheid.nl/onderwerpen/betrekkingen-met-nederland/overzicht-landen-en-gebieden/noord-korea|title=Betrekkingen Nederland – Noord Korea|publisher=Rijksoverheid|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170905140358/https://www.rijksoverheid.nl/onderwerpen/betrekkingen-met-nederland/overzicht-landen-en-gebieden/noord-korea|archive-date=September 5, 2017|url-status=dead|access-date=September 5, 2017}}</ref> There is little economic interest between the two countries. The most recent data about trade between the two countries dates back to 2011, and showed a decline.{{pb}}While the Netherlands does not have a bilateral development relationship with North Korea, it does participate in several humanitarian projects through the [[UN]], [[EU]] and the [[International Red Cross]]. In addition, [[Wageningen University and Research Centre]] and the Academy of Agricultural Sciences in Pyongyang are working together on several projects concerning food safety and recent developments in potato farming.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Norway}}\n|<!--Date started-->\n|See [[North Korea–Norway relations]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Poland}}\n|<!--Date started-->October 16, 1948\n|See [[North Korea–Poland relations]]{{pb}}[[Poland]] maintains diplomatic and limited trading (fishing) relations with North Korea after relations between the two countries began on October 16, 1948. Poland maintains an embassy in Pyongyang, with economic relations between the two countries currently maintained at the symbolic level of trade and sailing co-operation<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.krakowpost.com/9717/2015/07/the-strange-history-of-north-korean-polish-relations|title=The strange history of North Korean-Polish relations|last=Sedia|first=Giuseppe|date=July 17, 2015|work=[[Krakow Post]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151021140342/http://www.krakowpost.com/9717/2015/07/the-strange-history-of-north-korean-polish-relations|archive-date=October 21, 2015|url-status=live|access-date=November 9, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.msz.gov.pl/KOREANSKA,REPUBLIKA,LUDOWO-DEMOKRATYCZNA,(KOREA,POLNOCNA),20995.html |title= Ministerstwo Spraw Zagranicznych - Portal Gov.pl|website=www.msz.gov.pl |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090223080019/http://www.msz.gov.pl/KOREANSKA%2CREPUBLIKA%2CLUDOWO-DEMOKRATYCZNA%2C%28KOREA%2CPOLNOCNA%29%2C20995.html |archive-date=February 23, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.pl/web/dyplomacja|title=Ministerstwo Spraw Zagranicznych - Portal Gov.pl|website=Ministerstwo Spraw Zagranicznych|access-date=December 29, 2022|archive-date=May 1, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190501232418/https://msz.gov.pl/pl/informacje_konsularne/ostrzezenia/|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Portugal}}\n|<!--Date started--> Suspended October 11, 2017\n|See [[North Korea–Portugal relations]]{{pb}}[[Kim Yong-nam]] has made statements affirming the good relationship between the two countries, such as the condolences he gave then-President [[Jorge Sampaio]] when [[Francisco da Costa Gomes]] died,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kcna.co.jp/item/2001/200108/news08/03.htm|title=Past news|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141012063125/https://www.kcna.co.jp/item/2001/200108/news08/03.htm|archive-date=October 12, 2014|url-status=dead|access-date=February 19, 2015}}</ref> and the congratulations he extended to President [[Aníbal Cavaco Silva]] after he won the Portuguese elections.<ref>http://www.zibb.com/article/3400207/North+Korean+No+sends+greetings+to+Portuguese+president{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> In 2017, Portugal cut diplomatic ties with North Korea.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20171011000374|title=Portugal cuts diplomatic ties with N. Korea: report|date=October 11, 2017|access-date=October 21, 2017|archive-date=July 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200731165325/http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20171011000374|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Romania}}\n|<!--Date started-->November 3, 1948\n|See [[North Korea–Romania relations]]{{pb}}The [[People's Republic of Romania]] and North Korea established diplomatic relations on November 3, 1948.{{sfn|Wertz|Oh|Kim|2016|p=3}} The two states had little contact until [[Nicolae Ceaușescu]] and [[Kim Il Sung]] met in 1971 as part of Ceaușescu's Asian tour.<ref name=\"Post2014\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OqIaBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA103|title=Narcissism and Politics: Dreams of Glory|last=Post|first=Jerrold M.|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2014|isbn=978-1-107-00872-4|location=Cambridge|page=103}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nknews.org/2018/11/comrades-no-more-north-korea-romania-relations-70-years-on|title=Comrades no more: North Korea-Romania relations, 70 years on|last=Rinna|first=Anthony V|date=November 20, 2018|work=[[NK News]]|access-date=November 21, 2018|archive-date=October 5, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211005191858/https://www.nknews.org/2018/11/comrades-no-more-north-korea-romania-relations-70-years-on/|url-status=live}}</ref> The two were close allies,<ref name=\"Oberdorfer\" /> and got along both in terms of political and personal relations.<ref name=\"Gabanyi2000\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FaUsAQAAIAAJ|title=The Ceauşescu cult: propaganda and power policy in communist Romania|last=Gabanyi|first=Anneli Ute|publisher=The Romanian Cultural Foundation Publ. House|year=2000|isbn=978-973-577-280-2|page=93}}</ref> During the trip, Ceausescu took a liking to North Korea's ''Juche'' ideology. This experience contributed to his formerly liberal stance [[July Theses|taking a turn]] for totalitarianism.<ref name=\"Post2014\" /> It was the first of many times Ceaușescu would visit Pyongyang.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bKq6AAAAIAAJ|title=Vantage Point|publisher=Naewoe Press|year=1988|page=20|chapter=Romanian President Visits Pyongyang}}</ref>{{pb}}Both countries host embassies to one another. Since the [[Romanian Revolution]], contact between the two countries has been extremely limited.{{sfn|Wertz|Oh|Kim|2016|p=2}}\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Russia}}\n|<!--Date started-->October 12, 1948\n|See [[North Korea–Russia relations]] [[File:Kim Jong-un and Vladimir Putin (2019-04-25) 05.jpg|thumb|North Korean Leader [[Kim Jong Un]] (left) and Russian President [[Vladimir Putin]] (right), April 2019.]]{{pb}}Russia and North Korea maintain friendly relations and Russia is generally seen as the second most important ally of North Korea after China. Russia–North Korea relations are generally determined by [[Russia]]'s strategic interests in Korea and the goal of preserving peace and stability in the Korean peninsula. Russia's official position is by extension its stance on settlement of the [[North Korean nuclear crisis]].{{pb}}North Korea voted against a [[United Nations General Assembly Resolution ES-11/1|U.N. resolution]] calling on Russia to end its [[2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine|invasion of Ukraine]].<ref>{{cite news|author=<!--Staff writer(s)/no by-line.-->|date=March 3, 2022|title=UN resolution against Ukraine invasion: Full text|language=en|magazine=[[Al Jazeera Media Network|Al Jazeera]]|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2022/3/3/unga-resolution-against-ukraine-invasion-full-text|access-date=April 24, 2022|archive-date=March 3, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220303234448/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2022/3/3/unga-resolution-against-ukraine-invasion-full-text|url-status=live}}</ref> In October 2024, reports emerged that North Korean soldiers were being trained in Russia, potentially to be deployed in Ukraine. \n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Serbia}}\n|<!--Date started-->1948\n|See [[North Korea–Serbia relations]]{{pb}}[[Serbia]] maintains friendly relations with North Korea, with [[North Korea–Yugoslavia relations|relations between SFR Yugoslavia and North Korea]] started in 1948 under the [[President of Yugoslavia|Yugoslav President]] [[Josip Broz Tito]]. In March 2017, North Korean Ambassador Ri Pyong Du visited [[Belgrade]] and affirmed North Korea's support of Serbia's position on [[International recognition of Kosovo|Kosovo]].<ref>\"Serbia Grateful to N. Korea for Stance on Kosovo\". B92.Net, B92, March 21, 2017.</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Slovenia}}\n|<!--Date started-->\n|[[Slovenia]] and North Korea have a bilateral relation that began in 1948, during the time of Yugoslavia.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Spain}}\n|<!--Date started-->\n| {{see also|North Korea–Spain relations|Raid on North Korea's embassy in Madrid}}In January 2014, North Korea opened an embassy in [[Madrid]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.larazon.es/detalle_normal/noticias/5147802/la-razon-del-domingo/kim-jong-un-en-espana#.Ut5kdLQ1iUk|title=Kim Jong Un en España|work=larazon.es|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221143738/http://www.larazon.es/detalle_normal/noticias/5147802/la-razon-del-domingo/kim-jong-un-en-espana|archive-date=February 21, 2014|url-status=live|access-date=February 19, 2015}}</ref> Following a [[2017 North Korea crisis|series of nuclear and missile tests]] by North Korea in 2017, Spain declared the North Korean ambassador, Kim Hyok Chol, ''persona non grata'' on September 18.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nknews.org/2017/09/spain-declares-north-korean-ambassador-persona-non-grata|title=Spain declares North Korean ambassador persona non grata|author=Leo Byrne|date=September 18, 2017|work=[[NK News]]|access-date=September 18, 2017|archive-date=September 26, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170926095720/https://www.nknews.org/2017/09/spain-declares-north-korean-ambassador-persona-non-grata/|url-status=live}}</ref>{{pb}}On the afternoon of February 22, 2019, ten perpetrators, mostly Korean, broke into the North Korean embassy according to Spanish police. Spain's [[National Intelligence Centre (Spain)|National Intelligence Centre]] suspected that at least some of the perpetrators had ties to the American [[Central Intelligence Agency]] and South Korea's [[National Intelligence Service (South Korea)|National Intelligence Service]]. Embassy staff were beaten during interrogation. After one staff member managed to escape and caught the attention of a resident in the neighbourhood, the police were called. Officers arriving at the scene tried to enter the embassy but were refused by a man who claimed there was no cause for alarm. Soon after, two vehicles belonging to the embassy left and afterwards were abandoned nearby. The perpetrators had taken computers and mobiles phones. Spain's authorities suspect the attack was done in order to obtain information on Kim Hyok Chol who was part of a delegation which attempted to negotiate nuclear disarmament with the [[United States Special Representative for North Korea]] [[Stephen Biegun]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-spain-northkorea-idUSKCN1QG1QJ|title=Spain investigates raid on North Korean embassy: sources|newspaper=Reuters|date=February 27, 2019|via=www.reuters.com|access-date=January 2, 2020|archive-date=January 2, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200102205922/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-spain-northkorea-idUSKCN1QG1QJ|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://elpais.com/elpais/2019/03/13/inenglish/1552464196_279320.html|title=CIA implicated in attack on North Korean embassy in Madrid|first1=Miguel|last1=González|first2=Patricia Ortega|last2=Dolz|date=March 13, 2019|via=elpais.com|access-date=March 13, 2019|archive-date=March 13, 2019|archive-url=https://archive.today/20190313181049/https://elpais.com/elpais/2019/03/13/inenglish/1552464196_279320.html|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://elpais.com/politica/2019/03/12/actualidad/1552422470_906307.html|title=Policía y CNI vinculan con la CIA a dos asaltantes a la Embajada norcoreana en Madrid|first1=Miguel|last1=González|first2=Patricia Ortega|last2=Dolz|newspaper=El País|date=March 13, 2019|via=elpais.com|access-date=March 13, 2019|archive-date=April 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200413103734/https://elpais.com/politica/2019/03/12/actualidad/1552422470_906307.html|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-47553804|title=Who attacked North Korea's Madrid embassy?|work=[[BBC News]]|date=March 13, 2019|access-date=March 15, 2019|archive-date=March 20, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190320021707/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-47553804|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/mar/13/spain-investigates-possible-cia-links-to-north-korea-embassy-break-in-madrid|title=Spain investigates possible CIA links to embassy break-in|first=Sam|last=Jones|newspaper=The Guardian |date=March 13, 2019|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/world/assailants-in-raid-at-north-korean-embassy-in-madrid-have-connections-to-cia-reports|title=2 suspects in North Korea embassy attack in Madrid have CIA 'connections:' reports|first=Lucia Suarez|last=Sang|date=March 13, 2019|website=Fox News|access-date=March 15, 2019|archive-date=March 15, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190315183719/https://www.foxnews.com/world/assailants-in-raid-at-north-korean-embassy-in-madrid-have-connections-to-cia-reports|url-status=live}}</ref> Spanish court released details of the probe into attack on the embassy, perpetrators soon after attack went to Portugal and boarded plane for the US. 7 individuals were identified from the group, among them Adrian Hong Chang, founder of [[Liberty in North Korea]] as leader of the group. Court disclosed details of before, during and after the raid of the embassy by the group which consisted of citizens from the US, Mexico and South Korea. The group attempted to convince one of the embassy attache to defect.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://elpais.com/elpais/2019/03/26/inenglish/1553610317_669827.html|title=Attackers behind assault on North Korean embassy fled to US via Portugal|first1=Fernando J.|last1=Pérez|first2=Óscar|last2=López-Fonseca|date=March 26, 2019|via=elpais.com|access-date=March 27, 2019|archive-date=March 27, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190327182232/https://elpais.com/elpais/2019/03/26/inenglish/1553610317_669827.html|url-status=live}}</ref> Arrest warrants for Hong Chang and another person were issued by Spanish authorities. The alleged group leader contacted [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/26/world/europe/spain-north-korea-embassy-attack.html|title=Break-In at North Korean Embassy: Spain Says Gang Stole Material and Offered It to F.B.I.|first=Raphael|last=Minder|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=March 26, 2019|access-date=March 27, 2019|archive-date=March 27, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190327172440/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/26/world/europe/spain-north-korea-embassy-attack.html|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/03/27/politics/adrian-hong-north-korea-madrid-intl/index.html|title=Mexican national accused of breaking into North Korea's Spanish Embassy|first=Joshua|last=Berlinger|website=CNN|date=March 27, 2019|access-date=January 2, 2020|archive-date=May 10, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190510182447/https://www.cnn.com/2019/03/27/politics/adrian-hong-north-korea-madrid-intl/index.html|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-spain-northkorea-idUSKCN1R71O0|title=Group claims responsibility for North Korea embassy raid as Spanish judge seeks extradition of intruders|newspaper=Reuters|date=March 27, 2019|via=www.reuters.com|last1=Binnie|first1=Isla|access-date=March 27, 2019|archive-date=March 27, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190327172439/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-spain-northkorea-idUSKCN1R71O0|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nknews.org/2019/03/cia-linked-madrid-embassy-invaders-alleged-to-have-assaulted-n-korean-diplomats/|title=CIA-linked Madrid embassy invaders alleged to have assaulted N. Korean diplomats &#124; NK News|date=March 27, 2019|access-date=March 27, 2019|archive-date=March 27, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190327164555/https://www.nknews.org/2019/03/cia-linked-madrid-embassy-invaders-alleged-to-have-assaulted-n-korean-diplomats/|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Sweden}}\n|<!--Date started-->\n|See [[North Korea–Sweden relations]]{{pb}}[[Sweden]] was the first [[Western bloc|Western country]] to open an embassy in North Korea. The embassy is located in Pyongyang, and \"Sweden serves as the interim consular [[protecting power]] for American, Finnish, Australian and Canadian interests in North Korea.\"<ref name=\"Embassies in North Korea\">[http://everything2.com/title/Embassies+in+North+Korea Embassies in North Korea] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170501062942/https://everything2.com/title/Embassies%20in%20North%20Korea|date=May 1, 2017}} everything2.com, read April 8, 2011</ref> The [[Swedish-Korean Association]] has friendly ties with North Korea government and works to promote solidarity with and support for it.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Switzerland}}\n|<!--Date started-->\n|See [[North Korea–Switzerland relations]]{{pb}}Switzerland is an active member of the [[Neutral Nations Supervisory Commission]] (NNSC), an international organization for the prevention of hostilities on the Korean peninsula. Switzerland conducts regular political dialogue with North Korea, the last meeting taking place in October 2011. North Korea maintains both an embassy in [[Bern]] and a permanent mission in [[Geneva]]. Switzerland's embassy in [[Beijing]] is accredited to [[Pyongyang]] but the Swiss also have a permanent office [[Swiss Agency for Development and Cooperation|for Development and Cooperation]] in North Korea, responsible for humanitarian aid.<ref>[https://www.eda.admin.ch/eda/en/home/representations-and-travel-advice/dpr-korea/switzerland-dpr-korea.html Bilateral relations Switzerland–North Korea] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180923113308/https://www.eda.admin.ch/eda/en/home/representations-and-travel-advice/dpr-korea/switzerland-dpr-korea.html |date=September 23, 2018 }} Federal Department of Foreign Affairs (FDFA). Retrieved September 5, 2017</ref>{{pb}}Cooperation in the domain of education was maintained but North Korea's interest to work closer with Swiss companies has been put on hold since May 2016, when the Swiss cabinet introduced \"considerably tighter sanctions\" to slow down North Korea's nuclear proliferation.<ref>[https://www.swissinfo.ch/eng/restricting-trade--cash-and-training_north-korea-faces-long-list-of-swiss-sanctions/42163396 North Korea faces long list of Swiss Sanctions] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170906133536/https://www.swissinfo.ch/eng/restricting-trade--cash-and-training_north-korea-faces-long-list-of-swiss-sanctions/42163396 |date=September 6, 2017 }} swissinfo.ch. Politics. Conflict. Retrieved September 5, 2017</ref> In the aftermath of North Korea's nuclear weapons test on September 3, 2017, Swiss Federal Councilor and President [[Doris Leuthard]] emphasized the need for renewed negotiations, and offered pertinent mediation services between the United States and North Korea.<ref>[https://de.nachrichten.yahoo.com/nordkorea-krise-die-schweiz-vermitteln-131809061.html Nordkorea-Krise: Die Schweiz will vermitteln] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170905190249/https://de.nachrichten.yahoo.com/nordkorea-krise-die-schweiz-vermitteln-131809061.html |date=September 5, 2017 }}(in German). euro news. Retrieved September 5, 2017.</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Turkey}}\n|<!--Date started-->2001\n|[[Turkey]] did not have any diplomatic relations with North Korea before 2001. In a statement made in 2001 in Beijing by the Turkish and North Korean embassies, Turkey officially recognized North Korea and on January 15, 2001, both countries established diplomatic relations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mfa.gov.tr/turkiye-kuzey-kore-siyasi-iliskileri.tr.mfa|title=Türkiye – Kuzey Kore Siyasi İlişkileri|work=T.C. Dışişleri Bakanlığı|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150219162926/http://www.mfa.gov.tr/turkiye-kuzey-kore-siyasi-iliskileri.tr.mfa|archive-date=February 19, 2015|url-status=dead|access-date=February 19, 2015}}</ref> Turkey is represented in North Korea through its embassy in [[Seoul]], [[South Korea]]. North Korea is represented in Turkey through its embassy in [[Sofia]], [[Bulgaria]].{{pb}}Turkey fought against North Korea during the [[Korean War]], in which approximately 487 Turkish soldiers died.<ref name=\"nknews\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nknews.org/2018/06/turkey-n-korea-begin-negotiations-over-turkish-soldier-remains/|title=Turkey, N. Korea begin negotiations over Turkish soldier remains|last=Zwirko|first=Colin|date=June 26, 2018|publisher=NK Consulting Inc|quote=Turkey and North Korea have begun negotiations over the return of remains for almost 500 Turkish soldiers killed during the Korean War, Turkish outlet Habertürk reported late Tuesday. The Turkish Ambassador to South Korea Ersin Erçin, who recently also became ambassador-at-large to North Korea, told Habertürk that Turkey began negotiating the return of remains with Pyongyang following the June 12 U.S.-DPRK summit in Singapore. Erçin described talks as the start of a process where Turkey would first provide DNA samples to North Korea to help identify 487 soldiers believed to have perished in DPRK territory during the 1950-1953 war.|access-date=June 26, 2018|archive-date=June 26, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180626135238/https://www.nknews.org/2018/06/turkey-n-korea-begin-negotiations-over-turkish-soldier-remains/|url-status=live}}</ref> In June 2018, Turkey and North Korea began negotiations to return the remains of deceased Turkish soldiers.<ref name=\"nknews\" />\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|United Kingdom}}\n|<!--Date started-->December 12, 2000\n|See [[North Korea–United Kingdom relations]]{{pb}}Following initial progress in [[North Korea–South Korea relations]], North Korea and the United Kingdom established diplomatic relations on December 12, 2000, opening resident embassies in London and Pyongyang. The United Kingdom provides English language and human rights training to North Korean officials, urging North Korea government to allow a visit by the UN Special Rapporteur for Human Rights, and it oversees bilateral humanitarian projects in North Korea.{{pb}}To mark the tenth anniversary of North Korea's relations with the United Kingdom, an edited version of the 2002 film ''[[Bend It Like Beckham]]'' was broadcast on North Korean state television on December 26, 2010. The [[List of Ambassadors from the United Kingdom to South Korea|British Ambassador to South Korea]], [[Martin Uden]], posted on [[Twitter]] that it was the \"1st ever Western-made film to air on TV\" in North Korea.{{pb}}Good relations between the two nations have been in existence as far back as 1966 when the [[North Korea national football team]] played in the [[1966 World Cup]] in [[England]]. North Korea team became the adopted team of [[Middlesbrough]] which was where they played their group games during the competition. [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] fans went on to support North Korea team in the next round of the tournament, with many travelling to [[Liverpool]] to watch the team against Portugal. In 2002, members of North Korea team returned to Middlesbrough for an official visit.<ref name=guardian-20100608>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2010/jun/08/north-korea-world-cup-middlesbrough |title=How little stars from North Korea were taken to Middlesbrough's heart |last=Taylor |first=Louise |newspaper=The Guardian |date=June 8, 2010 |access-date=May 31, 2020 |archive-date=November 4, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131104194205/http://www.theguardian.com/football/2010/jun/08/north-korea-world-cup-middlesbrough |url-status=live }}</ref>\n|}\n\n===Oceania===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:100%; margin:auto;\"\n! style=\"width:15%;\" |Country\n! style=\"width:12%;\" |Formal Relations Began\n!Notes\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|Australia}}\n|<!--Date started--> 1975 but lapsed, before resuming in May 2000\n|See [[Australia–North Korea relations]]{{pb}}Australia and North Korea maintain diplomatic relations.<ref>[http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/n-korea-to-close-its-lonely-embassy/story-e6frg6t6-1111115403914 \"N Korea to close its lonely embassy\"], ''The Australian'', January 26, 2008</ref> Neither country has a diplomatic presence in the other country, and relations are strained by disputes such as over North Korea's nuclear program and alleged drug trafficking.<ref>{{cite web|title=Democratic People's Republic of Korea |url=http://www.dfat.gov.au/geo/dprk/ |publisher=Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade |access-date=March 27, 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130404143005/https://www.dfat.gov.au/geo/dprk/ |archive-date=April 4, 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/4837484.stm |title=N Korean heroin ship sunk by jet |access-date=August 2, 2007 |date=March 23, 2006 |work=[[BBC News]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080215120319/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/4837484.stm |archive-date=February 15, 2008 }}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|{{flag|New Zealand}}\n|<!--Date started--> March 2001\n|See [[New Zealand–North Korea relations]]{{pb}}Relations between the two countries have been almost non-existent since the establishment of North Korea. During the 1950s, [[New Zealand in the Korean War|New Zealand fought against]] North Korea in the Korean War, siding with the United States and South Korea. Since then, New Zealand had little contact with North Korea until 2001, when New Zealand recognised the North Korean state in March 2001,<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.beehive.govt.nz/release/new-zealands-first-ambassador-north-korea | title=New Zealand's first Ambassador to North Korea | access-date=August 15, 2022 | archive-date=August 15, 2022 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220815080440/https://www.beehive.govt.nz/release/new-zealands-first-ambassador-north-korea | url-status=live }}</ref> followed by the [[Minister of Foreign Affairs (New Zealand)|New Zealand's Foreign Affairs Minister]] [[Phil Goff]] meeting his North Korean counterpart [[Paek Nam-sun]]. Diplomatic relations were established shortly thereafter. New Zealand has accredited its embassy in South Korea to North Korea as well.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mfat.govt.nz/Embassies/1-NZ-representatives-overseas/index.php|title=Embassies – New Zealand representatives Overseas|publisher=New Zealand Ministry of Foreign Affairs and Trade|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150226203311/http://mfat.govt.nz/Embassies/1-NZ-representatives-overseas/index.php|archive-date=February 26, 2015|url-status=live|access-date=February 19, 2015}}</ref> New Zealand [[Ambassador]] Patrick Rata is in charge of New Zealand's relations with both South and North Korea.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mfat.govt.nz/Embassies/1-NZ-representatives-overseas/0-embassies-list.php|title=Embassies – New Zealand representatives Overseas|publisher=New Zealand Ministry of Foreign Affairs and Trade|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150316191934/http://www.mfat.govt.nz/Embassies/1-NZ-representatives-overseas/0-embassies-list.php|archive-date=March 16, 2015|url-status=live|access-date=February 19, 2015}}</ref> New Zealand's Foreign Affairs Minister [[Winston Peters]] made a trip to Pyongyang on November 20, 2007. The Foreign Affairs Minister had talks with President [[Kim Yong-nam]] in his two-day visit to North Korea's capital. Areas in which New Zealand is looking to co-operate could include agriculture, training, and conservation.\n|}\n\n==International organizations==\nNorth Korea is a member of the following international organizations:\n{{div col}}\n* [[Animal Production and Health Commission for Asia and the Pacific]]<ref name=nkintheworld/>\n* [[Asia and Pacific Plant Protection Commission]]<ref name=nkintheworld/>\n* [[Asia-Pacific Broadcasting Union]]<ref name=nkintheworld/>\n* [[Asia/Pacific Group on Money Laundering]] (observer)<ref name=nkintheworld/>\n* [[Asia-Pacific Telecommunity]]<ref name=nkintheworld/>\n* [[Asian–African Legal Consultative Organization]]<ref name=nkintheworld/>\n* [[ASEAN Regional Forum]]<ref name=cia>{{cite web |url=https://www.cia.gov/the-world-factbook/countries/korea-north/ |title=CIA World Factbook – Korea, North |publisher=Central Intelligence Agency |access-date=February 24, 2019 |archive-date=August 12, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150812052526/https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/kn.html |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* [[Asia-Europe Meeting]]<ref name=nkintheworld/>\n* [[Bureau International des Expositions]]<ref name=nkintheworld/>\n* [[Centre for Agriculture and Bioscience International]]<ref name=nkintheworld/>\n* [[Codex Alimentarius Commission|''Codex Alimentarius'' Commission]]<ref name=nkintheworld/>\n* [[Common Fund for Commodities]]<ref name=nkintheworld/>\n* [[Conference on Disarmament]]<ref name=nkintheworld/>\n* [[Convention on Biological Diversity]]<ref name=nkintheworld/>\n* [[Federation Internationale de Football Association]] (FIFA)<ref name=nkintheworld/>\n* [[Food and Agriculture Organization of the Uni